[{'created': '2015-10-08 00:29:42.000000000', 'message': 'Use assert(Not)In instead of assertTrue/False

Neutron tests should use:

self.assertIn(value, list) and
self.assertNotIn(value, list)

instead of:

self.assertTrue(value in list) and
self.assertFalse(value in list)

because assertIn and assertNotIn raise more meaningful errors:

self.assertIn(3, [1, 2])
>>> MismatchError: 3 not in [1, 2]

self.assertTrue(3 in [1, 2])
>>> AssertionError: False is not true

To enforce this improvement, this patch is created.

Change-Id: I4a05ad5a5ff9674dd94cff8b11585fd39dc264b3
Related-Bug: #1218713
'}]
commit_message:
Use assert(Not)In instead of assertTrue/False

Neutron tests should use:

self.assertIn(value, list) and
self.assertNotIn(value, list)

instead of:

self.assertTrue(value in list) and
self.assertFalse(value in list)

because assertIn and assertNotIn raise more meaningful errors:

self.assertIn(3, [1, 2])
>>> MismatchError: 3 not in [1, 2]

self.assertTrue(3 in [1, 2])
>>> AssertionError: False is not true

To enforce this improvement, this patch is created.

Change-Id: I4a05ad5a5ff9674dd94cff8b11585fd39dc264b3
Related-Bug: #1218713

commit_message:
Add notes about stable merge requirements for sub-projects

It was pointed out the requirements around what is allowed to be merged
into stable Neutron sub-projects wasn't clear. This attempts to make
that a bit more refined so those who choose to participate in the Neutron
Stadium know these requirements.

Change-Id: I6d472f4d9458ce311199ded89dc2a81759d1efa5
Signed-off-by: Kyle Mestery <mestery@mestery.com>

commit_message:
Ensure the test data sample has correct signature

Set the timestamp to iso format and make sure the test data samples
generated by scripts under tools directory have the correct signature.

Change-Id: I1520450ae4e82459b73cc411a698a6faa91a40e0
Closes-Bug: #1499651
(cherry picked from commit b5a49e79e301e9543e1ae3adfcc961bbe21bd363)

commit_message:
configure Apache only when ceilometer-api is enabled

Currently, even though ceilometer-api service is disabled by user,
we still try to configure ceilometer-api in Apache if CEILOMETER_USE_MOD_WSGI
is not set to false. This patch adds a constraint to ensure we only
configure when ceilometer-api is enabled.

Change-Id: I3f2bab3f646f7df57c32db3251f811cb801d93de
Partial-Bug: #1508518

commit_message:
link breaks in upstream training page

Rst does not support inline bolded hyperlinking.
Resolved by unbolding before link and rebolding
following the link.

Change-Id: Ia6af895e174fe3b152111a9dba886eb4b9ee05f5
Closes-bug: 1510494

commit_message:
Update to include HA concepts in context of OpenStack

Added a paragraph to explain why high availability is not the
default set up and how it can be difficult to use in some cases.

Change-Id: I980a7e24a2ac11c10fe4bdcf7d517d9a5f94383a
Partial-Bug: 1414115

This commit fixes an issue with the tempest configuration when
TEMPEST_HAS_ADMIN is disabled. Without admin credentials tempest
is unable to create credentials at all so enabling tenant isolation
is not going to work. Previously devstack wasn't setting it one way
or the other when TEMPEST_HAS_ADMIN was set, which results in the

"}]
commit_message:
Ensure we disable tenant isolation without admin

This commit fixes an issue with the tempest configuration when
TEMPEST_HAS_ADMIN is disabled. Without admin credentials tempest
is unable to create credentials at all so enabling tenant isolation
is not going to work. Previously devstack wasn't setting it one way
or the other when TEMPEST_HAS_ADMIN was set, which results in the
default of being enabled. So jobs that try to run tempest without
admin were failing.

Change-Id: Iff496cb5cbf29f17c130cfad746b48d8547ca965

commit_message:
enable autodocumentation for utils module; docstring fixes

This commit adds the utils module to those for which Sphinx
automatically generates documentation from docstrings. (Many of the
functions here may be of little interest to users, but
`generate_temp_url`, at least, definitely deserves to be in the
documentation; in this way, this commit can be seen as a spiritual
companion to ca70dd9e.)

Also, a few markup errors and perceived infelicities in existing
docstrings are amended.

Change-Id: I8c66a23cb359d7dd9302a16459fad9825fedb690

commit_message:
Updated CIDR explations in intro_basic_networking.rst.

This is manual update according to #1497522 fix. #1497522 fix adds a check,
if subnet CIDR is D class or loopback, neutron-server will raise a error.

Change-Id: I3dcbf671d3c0edf8c1ac753b2af4053e259df9e9

commit_message:
Validate Src and Dest IP address in firewall rules

It is possible to create a firewall rule which has IPv4
as source addresses and IPv6 as destination addresses
(or vice versa). However, OpenStack does not yet support a
packet to contain both IPV4 and IPV6 at the same time.
This change introduces a validation check to guard against
such incorrect inputs at user level. This check has been
implemented to guard against incorrect inputs at user level.

Change-Id: I1d0273148557d8867491845c8c3edf590a3cc482
Closes-Bug: #1501152

commit_message:
Add support to deploy the PowerVM networking driver

A new configuration attribute has been added in order to deploy PowerVM
driver. If the new attribute is enabled, it will auto set other attributes and
automatically include the PowerVM recipe. By default, the drivers will be
downloaded from source code on Stackforge. Another configuration attribute
allow to download from a public package repository

TODOS
- update openstack-network templates for PowerVM specific configuration

Change-Id: I1896f61f49b16ab5c20bfed7131601c45b034f29
Implements: blueprint openstack-powervm
Depends-On: Id8779f901a4129cf3ed7cb91e58d481887db2cc2

commit_message:
Disable shelve/snapshot/cinder when running Tempest with libvirt+lxc

The libvirt+lxc backend in nova does not support shelve, image snapshot
or any volume-related actions (so pretty much anything to do with
cinder), so we need to configure tempest to not run tests that hit those
operations/service when using libvirt/lxc.

This is part of an overall effort to get a CI job running for nova with
the libvirt+lxc configuration per:

Ic07c39e219121ba6b8b20de2b83a193bb735133d

Change-Id: I4decfcc5a5dfbabdecb3eb9fc93f1d1d6c2af805

commit_message:
Remove sudo from mkdir in $STACK_USER folder

This fails in the environment where sudo does not have permissions to
write in /home/$USER folder, e.g. [1]

Also clean-up the comment/variable usage a bit; the location isn't
actually variable at all (and that's fine, but we don't need a global
here)

[1] http://144.76.193.39/ci-artifacts/228979/10/Nova-ML2-Sriov/console.html.gz

Change-Id: I6807eae9d1c27219aa7c19de29f24fa851aa787c

commit_message:
Introducing docker changes to openstack-telemetry

This includes cookbook-openstack-telemetry changes required to enable
monitoring of docker type computes. 

Implements: blueprint container-metrics

Change-Id: I60b7d7097cad742f3b1c7a79b86d312b907d5d0c

commit_message:
Mechanism to disable cleaning in lib/ironic

Even though it is advised to enable cleaning in Ironic, cleaning
takes a lot of time and isn't suitable in developer testing
environments. There should be a mechanism to disable cleaning in
Ironic for developers who want to disable it.

Change-Id: Id3c1f1b801f78d66c21258baa84a03ef1bbcf5c2
Closes-Bug: 1510794

commit_message:
Make [baremetal]active_timeout configurable for tempest

This commit makes it possible to configure
[baremetal]active_timeout for tempest. This is required when
a real bare metal hardware is used for testing provisioning
with tempest. Real bare metal hardware times takes around
15-20 minutes to complete provisioning.

Closes-Bug: 1510786
Change-Id: Id2e7ca8d168d4badac155911bf4604103c5ad522

commit_message:
Make [scenario]ssh_user configurable for tempest

This commit makes it possible to configure
[scenario]ssh_user for tempest. This is required when
an image other than cirros image (like ubuntu or fedora
cloud image) is used for testing provisioning a real
bare metal hardware with tempest.

Change-Id: I46d304ebec9bb88f1b22f6a84d288ef6db36780b
Closes-Bug: 1510784

commit_message:
xapi-tools: fixes cache cleaner script

Fixes cache cleaner script by removing import of
driver and using session directly to call vm_utils.

There is no test included for this. Since this is out of nova
tree, adding tests is tracked in 1481705

Closes-Bug: #1481693

Change-Id: I25ee22777baecaf64de63a39d19e8f8f514f70b3

commit_message:
Prepare neutron "use_namespaces" option removal

The neutron use_namespaces option is deprecated since Kilo, it's time
remove it from neutron and devstack.

Related-bug: #1508188
Change-Id: I4feb2a15c7e1e4bfdbed2531b18b8e7d798ab3cc

some queries before we go ahead

I don't see any mention of the existing use of SWIFT_DEFAULT_BIND_PORT in lib/ironic?  That uses HOST_IP rather than SERVICE_HOST (and defaults to http, part of what this change fixes)

are we sure that this is the right thing to do wrt to that variable?

maybe the url fixups (service protocol, etc) should be split out of this change, and merged in with any fixes to the ironic urls, then have this follow on from that"}, {'account_id': 16982, 'date': '2015-09-08 13:39:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

What would be the benefit in separating that out?'}, {'account_id': 7118, 'date': '2015-09-09 21:46:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Use swift port variable in keystone and cinder

This patch alows specifiying a deviation of the swift default port 8080 with
variable SWIFT_DEFAULT_BIND_PORT. The created endpoints in keystone for
object-store and the backup_swift_url in cinder.conf will use variable
SWIFT_DEFAULT_BIND_PORT instead of the fixed port 8080.

Change-Id: I47bbcf77368c430718fb8f29b7de1ff305e64422
Closes-Bug: #1489767

commit_message:
Add new oslo.privsep library to oslo repos

A new project olos.privsep has been created but failes sdvm testing as
even though the library is added ro PROJECTS and LIBS_FROM_GIT it isn't
installed by devstack.

Add oslo.privsep to the install_oslo function

Change-Id: Ia4d56747d56dcfe50889ebbdf9d553df13e1b950

commit_message:
Fix Secrets Filter

Fixes the algorithm and mode parameters in the secrets list
command to return the correct secrets based on the correct
arguments.

commit_message:
Update to bashate 0.3.2

Bashate 0.3.2 has a few new checks -- firstly make sure some of the
plugins have #!/bin/bash, and fix up a couple of "local" changes that
were missed by I9c8912a8fd596535589b207d7fc553b9d951d3fe

Change-Id: I9e4b1c0dc9e0f709d8e76f9c9bf1c9478b2605ed

commit_message:
Set DEFAULT_OS_COMPUTE_API_VERSION to 2.5

The client currently implements support for microversions 2.2, 2.4 and
2.11.

According the nova API microversion history:

http://docs.openstack.org/developer/nova/api_microversion_history.html

2.3 just returns extra attributes in the response so it's not a problem
for the client. We should expose those at some point but it's not a
breaking change.

2.5 is a server-side only change since the client allows filtering
servers by IPv6 address but the server wasn't honoring that until 2.5.
There are no client side changes for that microversion.

2.6 is the first backwards incompatible microversion since it replaces
the old specific console APIs (RDP/serial/SPICE/VNC) with a new generic
remote-consoles API. The client must be updated to handle this since
requesting any microversion >=2.6 for consoles will fail right now. This
is exposed on the CLI right now because the CLI defaults to the 2.latest
microversion.

So even though the client actually supports the 2.11 microversion, we
shouldn't default to higher than 2.5 because we have gaps in handling
2.6->2.10.

This change fixes the default for the CLI by setting
DEFAULT_OS_COMPUTE_API_VERSION=2.5.

Partial-Bug: #1500688

Change-Id: I52074f9a3e7faa6a7a51c3fa9766100acf25dee2
(cherry picked from commit d045019f0f2d28f26730b3617f7d7b993506b6e8)

------------------------------------------------------------------------
The first change introduced a regression which is fixed in the following
squashed change to make the complete fix.
------------------------------------------------------------------------

Correct usage of API_MAX_VERSION and DEFAULT_OS_COMPUTE_API_VERSION

Commit d045019f0f2d28f26730b3617f7d7b993506b6e8 use the variables
API_MAX_VERSION and DEFAULT_OS_COMPUTE_API_VERSION with wrong way.

API_MAX_VERSION means the max version of client supported. This
variable only be changed when client support the new version. And
it's must bumped sequentially.

DEFAULT_OS_COMPUTE_API_VERSION is default value of option
'--os-compute-api-version', this value decided the default behaviour
of nova client. The nova client CLI behaviour should be that client
negotiate with server side to find out most recent version betweeyn
client and server. So the value should be '2.latest'. And it won't
be changed except we decided to change the default behaviour of nova
client CLI.

Change-Id: Iba9bfa136245bd2899c427ac0c231a30c00bd7f3
Closes-Bug: #1508244
(cherry picked from commit 28bf8ddb06a618bec280c9fbc21b4be6af2c1787)

commit_message:
Make sure router-gateway-set have consistent policy

For a non-admin user, now he can set router gateway by running
neutron router-gateway-set <router> <public_net>. But he can't
set router gateway by running
neutron router-gateway-set <router> <public_net> --disable-snat
He will get a HTTP 403 error and be told that "disallowed
by policy".
Neutron should keep these two actions be consistent.

The bug here is an old bug. More details of recent investigation
could be found at comment #5.

Change-Id: I78f106820ac3fc2364e91ebb368cefcc13b59cf3
Closes-Bug: #1296953

commit_message:
update doc to use new type PortOpt

We have supported a new type PortOpt, downstream will get benifit from
it, but our documents and docstrings still use old style of raw IntOpt
for port options. This patch updates those out dated docs.

Change-Id: I6d166903f591d3fe25336d133467148c01828b1b
ref: Icd4104ddfa2e36441e64aeccb0846712ce61b00f

commit_message:
remove url from v3 regions

the parameter "url" was removed from Keystone, it was only added
for one release as part of an experimental support for adding
service providers.

BackwardsIncompatibleImpact
Closes-Bug: 1506841

Change-Id: I7a62fbf1d9bfa8e6dd8d619e98c32b9860348d2e

commit_message:
Update help message for alarm-gnocchi-resources-threshold-create

Help message for '--aggregation-method' in
alarm-gnocchi-resources-threshold-create command is not precise.
The problem is that 'avg' is not a valid aggregation method in
gnocchi. This fix updates the help message.

Change-Id: I513b6fb9db9f96bfdd10391b6acd5c95e278f601
Closes-Bug: #1506549

Added processing /ec2 URL

With config option NOVA_USE_MOD_WSGI=True nova-ec2-api handles
requests on /ec2 URL.

commit_message:
Add a "bandit" target to tox.ini

This will allow us to find potential security issues, such as those fixed by
52e624891fc500c8ab9f3f10ef45258ce740916a and
c4a7ac0b653543e8a3ba10060cabdb114fb6672b .

Change-Id: I21aa0ca79232784069e55da46920eb43250d8939

commit_message:
remove unnecessary use_stderr=True in __init__.py

Since it is already set by unit/__init__.py, it's not necessary to do it
again in sub directories. Follow the same style done by neutron.

Change-Id: I811a5cfe40e124da03000f59f854f9fa657e9018

commit_message:
Use assertIsNone instead of assertEqual(None, ***)

Instead of using assertEqual(None, ***), developers should
use assertIsNone(***) to have more clear messages in case of failure.

Closes-Bug: #1510006
Change-Id: Ib3d09ed651877569a9b940da97662489885f18e9

commit_message:
Template: OSCI impact moved under Infra impact

OSCI is now part of Fuel project infrastructure, so relevant questions
in the spec template were moved under Infrastructure impact, and a
separate section for OSCI impact was removed.

Following 8.0 specs updated for the new structure:
* build-fuel-rpm-packages-for-centos7

Change-Id: Ibd99c9de0ca1a4c8f8e6a2e4eb1bb5d91ba105a4

commit_message:
Clear out NPIV metadata on reschedule

When a VM reschedules on to a different host, the NPIV metadata was
sticking around, and this caused an issue with the new host when the VM
landed on it.

This change clears out the system metadata on a full terminate of the
NPIV connection.  A full terminate is when the VM is being destroyed.

This should make the spawn on a new host fully 'fresh'.

Change-Id: I35348bbfffc8cb4693e6d0822e7a0c6ff42de032
Closes-Bug: 1510251
(cherry picked from commit b8199619f27dd1bd488b13584ddc59092af764a5)

commit_message:
Deprecate upgrade (that now is moved to initialize)

Perform part one of the rename of persistence backend upgrade
to initialize by putting a debtcollector decorator on the
existing upgrade method and having it proxy into the new and
more appropriately named initialize method.

For the existing in-built backends have the proxy not be
needed (and just rename there overrides of upgrade to now
use/override this new initialize method). All other existing
further usage still calls into the upgrade method so that any
user created persistence backends continue to operate
for a release (until we remove the upgrade method completely).

Part of blueprint storage-initialize-instead-of-upgrade

Change-Id: I8d8ae9305d82a6825c919011f35f5943681a4a60

commit_message:
Revisit the structure of the specs repo

Instead of having a per-release backlog directory, create
a top level one that holds the last release backlog. In
a healthy project this directory is really meant to be
empty or only temporary filled.

For specs that are two releases older, the content will
be moved to an 'archive' directory, purely for the record.
Hopefully this one too will be empty.

API and Juno incubator were moved to a miscellanea
directory to finish off the cleanup.

Finally, some blueprints completed and therefore were
moved to the Liberty directory.

Change-Id: I972a9a56c038864d9c91ead6944c6b9355916668

commit_message:
[WIP] lb: Separate agent loop from linuxbridge specific code

making methods private
Introduce and use agent constants.
Rename get_tap_devices to get_devices and move it to BridgeManager.
Move out agent_state configurations to BridgeManager
Rename br_mgr to mgr
moving rpc callbacks to LinuxBridgeManager
Moving config options to bridgemanager
move remove_port_binding into bridgemanager
move agent_id creation into bridgemanager

fixing functional and unittests

Change-Id: I0681eb32ad7f20e15a95ce919bb5c19646ca5861

commit_message:
Baymodel update should accept both uuid and name

Baymodel update should accept both uuid and name as
options. In its current state of art that doesn't seem
to be the case as only UUID is accepted.

Change-Id: I0c0ec32db3c111186b7a9ca2b2adceb9a7728ba9
Closes-Bug: #1501537

commit_message:
Don't use python-novaclient 2.33.0

Commit Iec7247b715c38c29910b30e76413cead4e951a37 changed behaviour with
exceptions. It will cause failures when python-novaclient users except
old exceptions to be raised. Nova team should fix this issue in a future
versions.

Change-Id: Ie7aee36efc5f2fa8138736406cada3b6c088f3f1

commit_message:
Handle correct exception raised by python-novaclient

We need to hanle both novaclient.exceptions.RequestTimeout
and requests.Timeout to make it works with a different
python-nocaclient versions.

Change-Id: Ib58101f12c87653aef97e055d22542acbeeee4a7
Closes-Bug: #1510790

commit_message:
Add toggle to run Heat API services via Apache2

Add templates for running Heat API services via
apache mod_wsgi. Also add appropriate functions to
lib/heat for configuring Heat.

Change-Id: I1bdd678c44ddfa616a9db7db85ff6f490ff08947

commit_message:
Add missing 'noop' checks to fuel-* projects

After gate jobs for master branches of fuel projects were enabled
recently, missing 'noop' checks prevented merges to stable/* branches
of those projects.

* Add 'noop-jobs' template to a number of fuel-* projects
* Change 'noop' gate to 'noop-jobs' template for fuel-menu

Change-Id: I3324694805a65f78daf69671ecb1244f9e193064

commit_message:
Add x and y axis tick formats

This allows us using d3 formats on our charts, simplifying our
controllers. This will help us avoiding adding formatting logic inside
our controller (i.e. multiplying percentages by 100).

Change-Id: Ia42fc20cc5e01433b899b2008088f1dcdc6646c0

commit_message:
Add retries for Cisco FCZM client CLI _cfg_save

Previously this config update would break if there were other changes
happening that were not completed yet. An easy work-around is to just
retry if it fails to apply the configuration update. There is already
code in place to handle this, but it doesnât actually work correctly.

Instead of fixing it Iâve switched over to using the utils.retry
decorator to do the retries.

Closes-Bug: #1482398

[{'created': '2015-10-21 13:15:22.000000000', 'message': 'Cloud Admin Guide: Shared File Systems updated information

After the technical review the Shared File Systems service
documentation in the Cloud Admin Guide needed to be updated.

Read and fixed some typos and wrong English construstions in
the sentances of all sections. Also updated the following info:

* Removed references to the Generic driver, because it is default
  only on Devstack.
* Added info that with StandaloneNetworkPlugin the Shared File Systems
  service can be configured without Networking and Compute services.
* Added export pathes for GlusterFS and HDFS.
* Added notes what driver in what mode you use in examples and a noted
  what modes exist and can be configured.
* Added a console sample for "manila rate-limits" command and described
  how to add rate limits.
* Added information what is a quota class and its purpose.
* Added second purpose of the share types.
* Removeed '/etc/manila/' in manila.conf file, because its path can be
  customly changed.
* Said that consistency groups is the experimental part of API starting
  with Liberty release.
* Updated a sample in shared_file_systems_multi_backend.html file.

commit_message:
Cloud Admin Guide: Shared File Systems updated information

After the technical review the Shared File Systems service
documentation in the Cloud Admin Guide needs to be updated.

Read and fixed some typos and incorrect English constructions in
the sentences of all sections. Fixed indentations in code, tip
and note directives. Also updated the following info:
* Removed references to the Generic driver, because it is default
  only on Devstack. And even for Devstack the default driver is going
  to be changed.
* Divided 'Create share' subsection on 3 subsections: added general
  concepts and info of creating a share in 2 back end modes.
* Added info that with StandaloneNetworkPlugin the Shared File Systems
  service can be configured without Networking and Compute services.
* Added export paths for GlusterFS and HDFS.
* Added notes what driver in what mode you use in examples and a noted
  what modes exist and can be configured.
* Added a console sample for "manila rate-limits" command and described
  how to add API rate limits.
* Removed information and samples about a quota classes because they are
  not used in the Shared File Systems service and are not working
  properly for the current moment (in Liberty release).
* Added second purpose of the share types.
* Removed '/etc/manila/' in manila.conf file, because its path can be
  customly changed.
* Said that consistency groups is the experimental part of API starting
  with Liberty release.
* Updated a sample in shared_file_systems_multi_backend.html file.
* Removed 'Storage' from the Shared File Systems service official name
  according to [1] document.

[1] http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/governance/tree/reference/projects.yaml

Change-Id: I0530ea3c6bf74311e271cdabca26cd10afcddc92
Closes-Bug: #1508457

'}]
commit_message:
Block python-novaclient 2.33.0

novaclient change 2961e82bfa6e375ac3c17933fac532ed316ac976 broke cinder
unit tests since it changed a public exception that was being raised to
a new type, which is a backward incompatible change and should only be
done in a major version release.

Cinder is working around this temporarily with change
99dc6d34754954a27f6998406a94743c41b93981. This is also failing cinder
tests on stable/liberty though and rather than backport the workaround
in cinder we should fix novaclient either via revert:

I368728588e5997eef860a168539eb66c58f2e72a

Or by making the new exception in novaclient extend the old exception:

I15cbc8f88fd04c86dc46c9587ff631a34e040ff7

And release either of those in a new version of novaclient that both
master and stable/liberty can consume.

Related-Bug: #1510790

Change-Id: I6e7657b60308b30eed89b269810c1f37cce43063

commit_message:
Nuke project priorities

It is too difficult and time consuming to track this by hand and
the section essentially duplicates information that's avaialable
in Launchpad.

The idea of highlighting who does what in a cycle is nice, but
this needs some more thinking.

For now, kill the section, which strikes as odd amongst the
other content of the landing page.

Change-Id: I78f18ed8418f01599fd6acb58317c70bb7f633e1

commit_message:
Block python-novaclient 2.33.0

novaclient change 2961e82bfa6e375ac3c17933fac532ed316ac976 broke cinder
unit tests since it changed a public exception that was being raised to
a new type, which is a backward incompatible change and should only be
done in a major version release.

Cinder is working around this temporarily with change
99dc6d34754954a27f6998406a94743c41b93981. This is also failing cinder
tests on stable/liberty though and rather than backport the workaround
in cinder we should fix novaclient either via revert:

I368728588e5997eef860a168539eb66c58f2e72a

Or by making the new exception in novaclient extend the old exception:

I15cbc8f88fd04c86dc46c9587ff631a34e040ff7

And release either of those in a new version of novaclient that both
master and stable/liberty can consume.

Conflicts:
        global-requirements.txt

Related-Bug: #1510790

Change-Id: I6e7657b60308b30eed89b269810c1f37cce43063
(cherry picked from commit 9b1dcacf44a39708fa666f7b23030d7c2a25f2ff)

commit_message:
Remove novaclient.v1_1 module

A long time ago in a galaxy far far away...this module was deprecated
(see 0a60aae852d2688861d0b4ba097a1a00529f0611 for more details) and
it's time to remove it(one full release of deprecation (Liberty) is 
ended).

Also, let's stop testing compute-api-version=1.1 .

Change-Id: I2ce177d8074921a54b4e3d1bfe3b794a80df9358

Prior to this patch, datasetService did not find the log paths that
'stackviz-export' and 'gulp data' generated. This commit adds the

Change-Id: Ie88d30a0844cea57cefed6b22265ccfd6050b3a9

commit_message:
Fix datasetService to find tempest log paths

Prior to this patch, datasetService did not find the log paths that
'stackviz-export' and 'gulp data' generated. This commit adds the
prefix 'data/' to all GET calls in datasetService to ensure that the
log files are found.

Change-Id: Ie88d30a0844cea57cefed6b22265ccfd6050b3a9

LGTM'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2015-10-27 18:13:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

As the bug points out, Idc0dfbbe1887e11166acb7d989dd5466751761af removed get_all usage and made it private for the zookeeper driver, so nothing is using the public get_all.

There is some debate in Idc0dfbbe1887e11166acb7d989dd5466751761af about whether or not it should be used, but those arguments are also talking about future implementations and direction/design for the service group API, and I don't see a point in leaving unused code in for that - it can always be added back if needed."}, {'account_id': 16907, 'date': '2015-10-27 20:24:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Indeed. And it's a bit more than just unused because if someone were to call it, it would explode because none of the drivers (or base class) implement the get_all method.

https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/75ecc63db95faf5704020f4974bda1a8d8f652c8/nova/servicegroup/api.py#L98'

Thanks for the review!"}, {'account_id': 15888, 'date': '2015-10-28 08:34:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 9569, 'date': '2015-10-28 11:26:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Hmm.. Sorry, but my patch was first https://review.openstack.org/#/c/214629/4 . I uploaded it 19 Aug. Actually I created bug #1502107 for this patch.'}, {'account_id': 10618, 'date': '2015-10-28 11:32:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I think you should abandon this patch. Sergey Nikitin created the same patch some time ago https://review.openstack.org/#/c/214629/4 but for unknown reasons the patch wasn't shown in launchpad https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1502107."}, {'account_id': 16907, 'date': '2015-10-28 13:41:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Okie dokie, I'll abandon this patch. My apologies - I didn't know there was already a patch for this since it wasn't linked to in launchpad bug."}, {'account_id': 16907, 'date': '2015-10-28 13:42:17.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

duplicate patch'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2015-10-28 20:33:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Pro-tip: the original patch wasn't linked to the bug because it wasn't in the first patch set's commit message:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/214629/1//COMMIT_MSG

The tooling relies on it being correct in the commit message in the first patch set, otherwise you have to associate them manually in launchpad."}]

commit_message:
Remove unused method API.get_all

The get_all method in the service group API class isn't used, and none
of the drivers implement the get_all method it calls.

Change-Id: I6b0d9c76ab35d31662ea13d83e3f69bf7ec8f9c5
Closes-Bug: #1502107

commit_message:
Fail Sphinx build on warnings

By setting pbr.warnerros = True, Sphinx will fail the build on any
warnings ensuring the documentation is properly maintained.

Due to a bug in pbr 1.8.0, the setting is not recognized when using
Sphinx < 1.3.1 https://bugs.launchpad.net/pbr/+bug/1496882

Proposed a global-requirements.txt change for pbr:
   https://review.openstack.org/225333

Enable pbr.warnerrors

Fix Sphinx warning:

Include readme in the index page, albeit with a depth of 1. Most of
/README.rst is redundant with the doc, you might want to phase it out in
favor of pointing to http://docs.openstack.org/developer/mistral/

Depends-On: I3e0a9b625d99d2beb117554948ea738a8fb9047b
Change-Id: I15f93b3864a4961b58f4c787d7954a5d215b6a17

[{'created': '2015-10-02 17:47:36.000000000', 'message': "Set DEFAULT_OS_COMPUTE_API_VERSION to 2.5

The client currently implements support for microversions 2.2, 2.4 and
2.11.

According the nova API microversion history:

http://docs.openstack.org/developer/nova/api_microversion_history.html

2.3 just returns extra attributes in the response so it's not a problem
for the client. We should expose those at some point but it's not a
breaking change.

2.5 is a server-side only change since the client allows filtering
servers by IPv6 address but the server wasn't honoring that until 2.5.
There are no client side changes for that microversion.

2.6 is the first backwards incompatible microversion since it replaces
the old specific console APIs (RDP/serial/SPICE/VNC) with a new generic
remote-consoles API. The client must be updated to handle this since
requesting any microversion >=2.6 for consoles will fail right now. This
is exposed on the CLI right now because the CLI defaults to the 2.latest
microversion.

So even though the client actually supports the 2.11 microversion, we
shouldn't default to higher than 2.5 because we have gaps in handling
2.6->2.10.

This change fixes the default for the CLI by setting
DEFAULT_OS_COMPUTE_API_VERSION=2.5.

Partial-Bug: #1500688

"}]
commit_message:
Set DEFAULT_OS_COMPUTE_API_VERSION to 2.5

The client currently implements support for microversions 2.2, 2.4 and
2.11.

According the nova API microversion history:

http://docs.openstack.org/developer/nova/api_microversion_history.html

2.3 just returns extra attributes in the response so it's not a problem
for the client. We should expose those at some point but it's not a
breaking change.

2.5 is a server-side only change since the client allows filtering
servers by IPv6 address but the server wasn't honoring that until 2.5.
There are no client side changes for that microversion.

2.6 is the first backwards incompatible microversion since it replaces
the old specific console APIs (RDP/serial/SPICE/VNC) with a new generic
remote-consoles API. The client must be updated to handle this since
requesting any microversion >=2.6 for consoles will fail right now. This
is exposed on the CLI right now because the CLI defaults to the 2.latest
microversion.

So even though the client actually supports the 2.11 microversion, we
shouldn't default to higher than 2.5 because we have gaps in handling
2.6->2.10.

This change fixes the default for the CLI by setting
DEFAULT_OS_COMPUTE_API_VERSION=2.5.

Partial-Bug: #1500688

Change-Id: I52074f9a3e7faa6a7a51c3fa9766100acf25dee2
(cherry picked from commit d045019f0f2d28f26730b3617f7d7b993506b6e8)

commit_message:
Fix Intermittant Unit Test Failure in Repositories

When sql_connection is null, then migration.init_config() will bail
with a run time error.  The default config value is null, so that
value needs to be overridden before migration.init_config() is called.
This usually works, either because an earlier test has overridden the
value or the test finds a barbican.conf file.  But, sometimes, it will
fail.

Change-Id: I5ffbcd037d7fd4d8841571c834378ecdf1d8d454

commit_message:
Clear out NPIV metadata on reschedule

When a VM reschedules on to a different host, the NPIV metadata was
sticking around, and this caused an issue with the new host when the VM
landed on it.

This change clears out the system metadata on a full terminate of the
NPIV connection.  A full terminate is when the VM is being destroyed.

This should make the spawn on a new host fully 'fresh'.

Change-Id: I35348bbfffc8cb4693e6d0822e7a0c6ff42de032
Closes-Bug: 1510251

[{'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2015-10-28 14:14:07.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2015-10-28 14:24:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Note that cinder went and approved a change (which I didn't see until after I proposed this revert) which handles both exception types now:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/239837/

However, that just fixes cinder, we don't know what other consumers of novaclient were broken by the change, so I think the revert is still justified, but we don't have to act as quickly now at least."}, {'account_id': 16907, 'date': '2015-10-28 14:27:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 9545, 'date': '2015-10-28 14:27:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2015-10-28 14:27:58.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 2243, 'date': '2015-10-28 14:30:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

I'm not as hard lined on the API change stuff that's been discussed as of late and don't have an issue with fixing it in Cinder and moving on.  But, your suggestion of extending the existing class is WAY better anyway.

I'm not sure about the Cinder change that was approved anyway, I'm not sure it will catch the old exception for compat use with old clients but this patch will answer that faster than me trying to open anything else in my browser from here :("}, {'account_id': 16907, 'date': '2015-10-28 14:33:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 9545, 'date': '2015-10-28 14:38:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2015-10-28 14:49:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I'm going to push an alternative change to novaclient to make RequestTimeout extend requests.Timeout since that class is meant to be inherited anyway, at least in how it's used in the requests library:

https://github.com/kennethreitz/requests/blob/v2.8.1/requests/exceptions.py#L46

So it's simply a marker, it doesn't have a status code or anything.  Then cinder can just continue to handle catching requests.Timeout and slowly be moved to using novaclient.exceptions.RequestTimeout if needed.

If at some point novaclient doesn't use requests internally, I think that would be a major version bump anyway and we can work through it if/when that happens.  In the meantime we should probably block novaclient 2.33 in g-r on master and stable/liberty and revert the cinder change on master."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2015-10-28 15:06:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Here is the alternative to avoid the revert:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/239963/

Also have a g-r block on 2.33 here:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/239964/'}, {'account_id': 13720, 'date': '2015-10-28 15:09:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Matt, I think the point of the previous patch was that novaclient must not explicitly depend on requests; i.e. we should be able to swap out requests for another library without breaking things. Extending the requests error classes won't resolve that issue.

Since this wasn't done earlier, we now have projects that depend on certain errors being returned to be requests errors. IMO the fix should be in the downstream projects, but I'm going to hold off -1 since this is summit time."}, {'account_id': 13720, 'date': '2015-10-28 15:12:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Apologies, I just saw the other patch. I agree that subclassing is a better solution right now.'}, {'account_id': 9545, 'date': '2015-10-28 15:16:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

g-r block for stable/liberty: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/239799/'}, {'account_id': 1736, 'date': '2015-10-28 15:30:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-28 15:38:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

Pratik, making these backward incompatible changes for a future requirement of possibly removing novaclient's dependency on requests is premature - there is no desire to do that right now as far as I know, and if we did, it'd probably be a major version release on novaclient anyway.

As pointed out in the other change, if we just subclass all of the requests exceptions in novaclient, what was then the point of the original change?  So I think the revert is most prudent and we can rethink the long term strategy here later when we're not breaking consumers of novaclient."}, {'account_id': 7253, 'date': '2015-10-28 16:11:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

I'll re-propose a patch with the requests inheritance as soon as this merges."}, {'account_id': 13720, 'date': '2015-10-28 16:12:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

The long term strategy is to decouple exceptions from other libraries from bubbling up in novaclient. There has already been much discussion about it here: https://bugs.launchpad.net/cinder/+bug/1510656. The consensus from that discussion wasn't specifically a future requirement, but to prevent exactly these kinds of errors as we get more OS projects that depend on novaclient."}, {'account_id': 13720, 'date': '2015-10-28 16:16:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Revert "Do not expose exceptions from requests library"

This reverts commit 2961e82bfa6e375ac3c17933fac532ed316ac976

This broke cinder unit tests that have a timeout test for novaclient
where they mock the requests library raising a Timeout exception. That
test expects to get a requests Timeout passed through but with the
change being reverted it was getting a RequestTimeout exception from
novaclient, which breaks the test and fails the gate runs.

We could change the cinder unit test to handle both the requests.Timeout
and the new novaclient RequestTimeout, but that's just papering over
the cinder failure, we wouldn't know what other clients are failing
in the same way because they have code working around the requests
exceptions getting passed through, so we should treat this like an API
change.

I'd be in favor of making the same change again iff the novaclient
exceptions extended the requests exception types so it would be transparent
to consumers, since novaclient.exceptions.RequestTimeout would be a
requests.Timeout via inheritance. But given the gate breakage and it being
summit week I'm inclined to revert first and think about a better long term
fix later when people are back to discuss.

Change-Id: I368728588e5997eef860a168539eb66c58f2e72a
Closes-Bug: #1510790

commit_message:
[packetary] Infrastructure

Introduce infrastructure:
* Executor (The Asynchronous task executor)
* ConnectionsPool (The pool of network connections)
* ResumeableStream - allows resume streaming when error occures

Change-Id: Ia68d60c2b9d685820a4c1916c8f1aa724f3a3f91
Implements: blueprint refactor-local-mirror-scripts
Partial-Bug: #1487077

commit_message:
[Sahara] Split EDP context

The Data Sources and Job Binaries contexts are now separated.
Now there is no need to set the Data Source when they are not required or
not supported by the Job type.

Implements-bp: split-sahara-edp
Change-Id: I64dd55138d89c5fefcc2b2c120906873153413f0

I'm sorry but I do not see a value in adding more states to Release. What is the *real* difference between "manageonly" and "notavailable"?

 IMHO it just complicates things - you need to how to work not with just one value "is_deployable" but now you need to work with three states in client, frontend and backend.'}, {'account_id': 14543, 'date': '2015-10-22 07:40:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

The difference between manageonly and not available release is as follows: not available - you cannot do anything with this release. Manage only - you can only manage existing clusters with this release, but you cannot create new ones. It was requested by support team.'}, {'account_id': 12200, 'date': '2015-10-22 07:52:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

Maciej, but what is the *actual* difference for nailgun? Also that something was requested by someone doesn't automatically mean that this makes sense."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-22 08:39:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change or one of its cross-repo dependencies was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of its repository. Please rebase the change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 10391, 'date': '2015-10-22 09:42:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

Sebastian,

Let me share a short story why we do have `state` and `is_deployable`.

A long time ago Fuel had an RHEL release, but we never distribute RHEL packages within master node. By design, Fuel was able to download them on behalf of users with provided credentials. So the `state` column was added, because we were needed to deal with different release states:

* ready for deployment
* not ready for deployment
* downloading

One day we stopped deal with RHEL, but the `state` field wasn't removed. It's become legacy. Everyone forgot about it. It wasn't used.

Eventually, we became interested in somehow marking release to be *manageable only*, so users won't be able to create new clusters of this releases, but will be able to manage old clusters of this release (add nodes, remove nodes, etc). That's where `is_deployable` field was introduced. If it's true - user's able to creanew new envs of this release, if not - they aren't able.

For the time being it worked fine. Until in Fuel 7.0 we stopped support CentOS. Obviously, it was impossible to use "is_deployable" field, since it meant "you can manage old clusters on this release".. and it was possible to create new envs in experimental. So we remembered about `state` field, and it was decided to use it to mark CentOS as unavailable.

Well, in my opinion the design of release states are over-complicated, and it would be easy to track its states in one field rather in two. Moreover, it looks confusing when


  state: unavailable
  is_deployable: true

How we should deal with it? It makes a little sense, because if release is unavailable then it obviously CAN'T be deployable.

So that's my thoughts. :)

You thoughts? You're against these changes?'}, {'account_id': 12200, 'date': '2015-10-22 10:06:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

@Igor:
Having two fields for managing states - it is obviously not acceptable and there are no doubts that we should get rid of one of them.

The only concern that I had is that if we really need three states, maybe simple bool (we can deploy new env, we cannot deploy new env) would be enough? In the end (if there will be no further changes) it will be like unavaiable == deploy, manageonly or notavaiable == do not deploy

Although it's true that those three states better describe the status of Releases. And they do not harm ;)


@Maciej: 
I've found one flaw (this is why I'm keeping my -1 here). Now 'manageonly' will be used to tell which release can be still used (in exisitng envs) after deploy. You need to correctly mark old releases with 'manageonly' during migration/upgrade. Remeber that in 7.0 CentOS must not have 'manageonly' as it is not available at all."}, {'account_id': 14543, 'date': '2015-10-22 15:02:53.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 8.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-22 15:34:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Verified+1

commit_message:
Replace release.is_deployable with release.state

is_deployable doesn't really give any additional information for a
release, it is removed. To make change API-backward-compatible, it is
retained as a property dependent on release.state.

New state is added - manageonly, for environments that are not able to
be deployed, but can still be managed.

Change-Id: I518a0114730a2f227c9ef035a376f9a90d3d5bbd
Closes-bug: #1503303
DocImpact

commit_message:
DO NOT MERGE: get a tempest run with devstack + lvm-backed lxc nova

Needed to see what the blacklist of tempest is going to be.

This explicitly blows up devstack setup if running with neutron
or nova-cells.

There are three main config changes:

1. Run with virt_type=lxc.
2. Run with images_type=lvm for lvm-backed lxc instances.
2. Run with volume_clear=none so we don't waste time zero'ing
   out the lvm disks.

There are two dependent nova changes:

1. The first makes the lvm-backed instance mounting work for lxc.
2. The second fixes a bug with linuxbridge re-assigning MACs which
   screws up networking to the guest VMs.

Depends-On: I5aae1e293832f7cff7bc00d793bcc86ededf5eec
Depends-On: Ibf5333516a4c5487a3ee7c662e07028789bdd286

Change-Id: I71cc1938dbaf2747683fd4f27122253c3d0761a5

commit_message:
Requires python-ordereddict only if Centos6

OrderedDict class is a part of collections module since at least
python2.7 which is default python version for Centos 7.
For making it possible to use this code both on python26
and on python27 we wrap ordereddict imports into try/except.

Change-Id: I877506a8f039e86480c287e03387b9a3689d870e

commit_message:
iPXE document about the existence of prebuilt images

Prior to this patch the Ironic documentation was only mentioning about
the images which are packaged by the supported distros and about compiling
an iPXE image from source.  This patch extends the documentation to talk
about the prebuilt images that are distributed by the iPXE project.

The patch also fixes the syntax of the note RST tag.

Change-Id: I3b4230e5a43e4db5268e1d0c2a1dcdf25ffac396

[{'created': '2015-10-28 15:04:57.000000000', 'message': 'Make RequestTimeout extend requests.Timeout also

2961e82bfa6e375ac3c17933fac532ed316ac976 added RequestTimeout and started
raising RequestTimeout instead of requests.Timeout which broke cinder
unit tests that expected to handle requests.Timeout but started getting
RequestTimeout.

Changing the type of exception raised from the client is a backward
incompatible change and should be handled gracefully, and would require a
major version bump.

We can get around this for now by making RequestTimeout extend
requests.Timeout so that cinder can still work with expecting that type
of exception.

If we want to decouple this later, it would have to be in novaclient 3.x.

commit_message:
Make RequestTimeout extend requests.Timeout also

2961e82bfa6e375ac3c17933fac532ed316ac976 added RequestTimeout and started
raising RequestTimeout instead of requests.Timeout which broke cinder
unit tests that expected to handle requests.Timeout but started getting
RequestTimeout.

Changing the type of exception raised from the client is a backward
incompatible change and should be handled gracefully, and would require a
major version bump.

We can get around this for now by making RequestTimeout extend
requests.Timeout so that cinder can still work with expecting that type
of exception.

If we want to decouple this later, it would have to be in novaclient 3.x.

Change-Id: I15cbc8f88fd04c86dc46c9587ff631a34e040ff7
Closes-Bug: #1510790

commit_message:
Add Fuel Master IP if configuring DNS settings post-deploy

Post-deploy settings should include Fuel Master IP as the
first nameserver entry. Adding it early on causes delays
in deployment (because it does not respond), but it gets
added later during puppet run when Cobbler is up and
running dnsmasq.

Change-Id: I733f9b616cacccab4a914cc5610b60be888abda4
Depends-On: I42fc5d3261fe7e6c4a996e9895710970fc721247
Related-Bug: #1503616

commit_message:
Add post-deployment rules for PXE network configuration

Fuelmenu should allow post-deployment configuration of
PXE network, but place the following restrictions:
* new_range must contain old_range in dhcp pool
* PXE interface must remain the same

For all intents and purposes, the changes are limited to
extending the range from the previously configured one.
A common use case of this would be if a user defined a /24
network for PXE, and then decided to change it to a /23
network. This would meet the user's needs and not impact
existing deployed nodes.

Change-Id: I42fc5d3261fe7e6c4a996e9895710970fc721247
Closes-Bug: #1503828

commit_message:
Hardcode part_power for swift ring builder

The default part_power for 3 controllers should
be 10. Previous deployments calculated the part_power
of 3 controllers to 10, so this should be preserved
for future deployments.

For custom deployments which require a different part_power,
it should be set in swift_hash in the key 'ring_part_power'.

Removed calc_ring_part_power provider because it will no
longer be used.

DocImpact: Should advise users before upgrading from a
prior release about swift ring part_power.
Change-Id: Ic7f8f6824712cc2bb5b530fe1300c9a3ac4ce302
Closes-Bug: #1498368

commit_message:
Support for freezer agent plugble storages on windows

added freezerc executable for windows
added for local storage
improved tar command to support different storages
ssh is NOT implemented in this version
changed paths to use os.sep instead of /
added ssh binaries and its dependencies
updated windows installation instructions in README

Change-Id: I34a151a0dd14fb925b80c5b0c409092730f59b89

commit_message:
Explicitly set fuel-library version to PRODUCT_VERSION

This works around a case where fuel-library has multiple
versions available, but we only want to ensure that the
version PRODUCT_VERSION is installed by anaconda.

Change-Id: I2681123ec508d11d90264f914fa25a68b6e5e7bb
Closes-Bug: #1509313

commit_message:
Wait for FC multipath devices to become writable

Sometimes the multipath devices would be read-only block devices which
would end up causing problems when anything tries to write to them. We
now will wait and rescan a few times to try and get them to become
read-write before moving on with the attach.

Change-Id: If3c17348f6a6e766f811fcd446c03c82e5c8a883
Partial-Bug: #1495701

commit_message:
Define fuel-library7.0 package explicitly in fuel-centos.ks

Since both fuel-library6.1 and fuel-library7.0 provides the same
package: `fuel-library` yum select those which has less
dependencies, in our case it's fuel-library6.1 which is wrong.

Related-change: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/231584/

Change-Id: I0bcb6b37e499a3d5275d1f2294de4bff0fdc42b6
Closes-bug: #1508579

commit_message:
Fix random name bug if task uuid is too short

If the task UUID passed to generate_random_name() was shorter than the
first set of Xs in the pattern, the UUID would be used which would
result in a random name that was too short and thus didn't match the
pattern. This fixes that.

Implements blueprint: consistent-resource-names
Closes-Bug: 1509402
Change-Id: I4f8a4415d565dbf737588a4db56fc2a6dfe893cc

commit_message:
Do not expose exceptions from requests library

Novaclient expects the requests library to always be able to get a
response back and doesn't handle other cases where it might raise
an exception even before the request is completed (e.g.
ConnectionError).

These exceptions should be captured and properly converted to some
native novaclient exception.

Change-Id: Iec7247b715c38c29910b30e76413cead4e951a37
Co-Authored-By: Kuo-tung Kao <jelly.k@inwinstack.com>
Closes-Bug: #1406586

commit_message:
[Ceilometer] Add check for compute existence

Currently all Ceilometer tests are skipped if there are no compute
nodes in cluster.

Added check for compute existence and now will be skipped only
those tests where compute is needed.

Change-Id: I2a3fd23d6cb7fb5c9528ff3eaf3fdf69cbf75957
Closes-bug: #1469188

commit_message:
Fix version override of Fuel release in dockerctl

Corrects options handling did not handle override
of version so that one can correctly use the
following commands:
dockerctl -V 8.0 start postgres
dockerctl --version 7.0 destroy nginx

The wrong variable was in the template leaving the
version defaulted to "", and then reverting to 8.0
as hardocded by the RPM. Switched to @release var
name.

Fixed varname for dockerctl config in hardcoded conf
distributed in the RPM so it does not get replaced.

Change-Id: Ia864b0a9843f927aa85945e5ab0b2da4bec3a440
Related-Commit: I28032852517ec8f7e959ad48a04621ec3e33fea1
Related-Bug: #1501368
Closes-Bug: #1510080

Add new percentage filter

Includes a new Angular filter which will help us formatting percentage
values correctly without bloating our controllers with multiplications
by 100.

commit_message:
Fixed generators support in fuel plugin environment_config.yaml

Fixed attributes processing mechanism in such a way that at the first step
instance editable metadata attributes are merged with plugin attributes and
only after that the resulting attributes dict goes through generator processing

Change-Id: I4bda81f323a3f77ae5ace3927ac5f157503822ee
Closes-bug: #1473452

commit_message:
Change the home-page url in setup.cfg

The current value for home-page in setup.cfg
which is launchpad url is replaced with openstack.org

Reason for change: All projects using generic homepage url
and also by crosschecking with ceilometermiddleware

Change-Id: Ifcd0251dd827b772db8434bc2059e50382f474a9

Windows support for freezer-agent

freezerc now is installed as a script on windows
support for swift, ssh, and local backups and restores
improve tar commands

commit_message:
Fixed issue with deprecation warning

We need to use another configuration file for fuelclient
and we also need to provide the ability to create new users
on fuel master node with the correct configuration file for
fuelclient.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I08fd7bf965af1552d16671636c4f706c5a2d6a11
Closes-Bug: #1458361

commit_message:
Backport ulimit setting to Juno

This backports the ulimit settings for rabbitmq and mariadb
into juno allowing the settings to be changed / updated as
needed.

There is no reference backport for this change. This is a 
functional backport to resolve customer issues with ulimit
setting for rabbitmq and galera.

Change-Id: I8633e4aa9fba99439ef1c3794b29dbd9c7eedd85
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

Hi Chris, 
Thanks for the review :)
During the create_and_list_security_groups, we are using cleanup from context which lists all resources under a tenant and delete one after the other. In this case, default is available in the lists which is not allowed.
But in the case of create_and_delete_security_groups we delete only the ones created in the scenario. Thus you would not see a problem.
I am thinking of solving this by handling it in cleanup context.'}, {'account_id': 6835, 'date': '2015-10-08 17:15:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Add Neutron Security Groups scenarios

This patch adds the following scenarios:
 * Create and list Neutron security groups
 * Create and delete Neutron security groups
 * Create and update Neutron security groups

Change-Id: Icd452f92a2be645354eb8f2f9c61ad57328f1863

commit_message:
Update VMs in the database on cluster reset

On cluster reset all VMs within nodes of this cluster
are destroyed. We need to drop 'created' flag for these
VMs.

Closes-Bug: #1491364
Change-Id: Ibc8ae542202013548f8d47ec6d925f82b00d5101

commit_message:
Enable retry for multiple force hosts

If there are multiple force hosts/nodes, retry filter will help
retry on the force hosts/nodes if there are VM boot failure.

Change-Id: I58c95f16e320a03d41988c860e18434412c475c3
Closes-Bug:1435156

commit_message:
Add check if VIP name already present in network config

Add check to 'assign_vips_for_net_groups_for_api' method of 7.0 network
serializer. The check detects data of particular VIP being overwritten
by VIP with the same name. In case it does specific error is raised.
Such situation may occur when plugins of the cluster introduce
conflicting network configuration (that is shown by added unit test).

The exception is caught in
ApplyChangesTaskManager.check_before_deployment that fails the
deployment process in such case.

Change-Id: Icdd6ed649d92ba5745d093a9612c2f30c082071c
Closes-Bug: #1487482

[{'created': '2015-09-22 13:23:44.000000000', 'message': "Don't use retries for puppet deployments by default

Granular deployment task with possibility for user
to control number of retries for any task now allow
Astute to decrease number of retries from 1 to 0 by default.

It will give us such benefits:

* fail fast: do not use useless retries for failed task;
* detect cases where we need to place retries inside task code;
* show us tasks with bad design from box.

For special it could be setup by hands.

Change-Id: I0b5645bdceb524f3b0e0135125c9a3f457fbc3b4
Closes-Bug: #1457887
"}]
commit_message:
Don't use retries for puppet deployments by default

Granular deployment task with possibility for user
to control number of retries for any task now allow
Astute to decrease number of retries from 1 to 0 by default.

It will give us such benefits:

* fail fast: do not use useless retries for failed task;
* detect cases where we need to place retries inside task code;
* show us tasks with bad design from box.

For special it could be setup by hands.

Change-Id: I0b5645bdceb524f3b0e0135125c9a3f457fbc3b4
Closes-Bug: #1457887

commit_message:
Fix mixin class clients

In patch I78b57d44b37c34cebadc2b72cf55b4f9405447a3
was added new clients methods for keystone resources.
As result it leads to error when we try to use role_assignments
properties.

Change-Id: I127863ee37f2cba487d6c66ec12a0035319f3fc2
Closes-Bug: #1509333

(fd and socket) causes StopIteration on reader at proxy server
on PUT object case.

And then, if the connection closed and proxy detects a lack of
data length, it will result in HTTPClientDisconnected.

The only reason why I leave test_client_disconnect as current

commit_message:
Add verification socket close causes StopIteration

This patch add a expositive test that closing connection
(fd and socket) causes StopIteration on reader at proxy server
on PUT object case.

And then, if the connection closed and proxy detects a lack of
data length, it will result in HTTPClientDisconnected.

The only reason why I leave test_client_disconnect as current
is Bill is now working for the change at

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/236007/

Change-Id: If68f752a2b0dd6cfad4d007ca5d155e6ffb378e5

commit_message:
avoid unnecessary inner join in get_resources() for SQL backend

To get distinct resource ids, we do a query on resource table which
inner join sample table, and apply filters on it.

Note that when sql_expire_samples_only is enabled, there will be
some resources without any sample, in such case we must use inner
join to avoid wrong result, no matter if there is a timestamp filter
or not.

But that option is disabled by default, so when there is no timestamp
filters, the inner join is unnecessary, we should avoid it to save
some RAM/CPU cost.

Change-Id: If85dbea15d42d42c6b0be7402c06f258e278b2eb
Closes-Bug: #1509677

Add neutron jobs to certification task arguments

Also minor issues fixed:
 - add neutron quota info only if neutron service is available
 - add missing task args to test command

commit_message:
GlusterFS: extend volume to the right path

Extend volume uses the wrong volume file path. It should
extend the active volume file path.

And set _active_volume_path as a common function, that
also change delete_volume() and backup_volume().

Closes-Bug: 1499452

commit_message:
Division result is wrapped to int().

In py27 sys.getsizeof(str(long_string)) / 1024 returns 
int value but in py34 it returns float value.

Due to this "if size_kb > size_limit_kb:" condition is
getting true and in py34  UT
"Size of 'input' is 0KB which exceeds the limit of 0KB"
error is occurred.

Partially-Implements: blueprint mistral-py3

Change-Id: I0c7a4bc316fcc67084d81f59cb1f6f3f9d1a8eef

commit_message:
Performance test timeout increased for PUT of DeploySelectedNodes

We have periodical failures of test_put_deploy_selected_nodes test
on the CI server. This failure is reproduced periodically in all
the time of job monitoring. Thus we can assume, that timeout value
is not optimal for our CI servers.
Thus acceptable timeout for put_deploy_selected_nodes increased
from 10 to 15.

Change-Id: I69f4e1b11394cbff110d473113574920a236f50b
Closes-Bug: #1498365

commit_message:
[WIP] Make the FwaaS API port based

The FwaaS API currently only focuses on firewalling at the Neutron
router level, which artificially limits where the Firewall API can be
utilized.

Part of the firewall router insertion specification[1] during the Kilo
cycle discussed eventually opening up the Firewall API model to deal
with ports, so this work is a spiritual successor of that paragraph
within the specification.

Additional work is being discussed on the etherpad[2] to make the
Firewall API more useful for users, and can be read for more context.

This commit will most likely break everything and explode in spectacular
fashion, but it is meant as a flag in the ground to rally around and
discuss further.

Migrations to the new data model can be done, by querying the router_ids
from the firewall insertion API extension that a firewall contains, and
creating the apropriate rows in the firewall_port_associations table,
while deployments that didn't have the firewall insertion API extension,
would require a more expensive query where all ports that a tenant owns
are assocated with a firewall policy. (I think).

[1]: http://specs.openstack.org/openstack/neutron-specs/specs/kilo/fwaas-router-insertion.html

[2]: https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/fwaas-api-evolution-spec

Change-Id: If2696b34dd872525e3994a1fe0c9b98698e49919

commit_message:
Add driver option for metering agent

metering agent uses different drivers for collecting statistics.
If driver option is not configurable, it will use Noop driver which doesn't
make much sense

Change-Id: Icc0766b0d61cad91c5a423f1ea384a8b59e2b2c2

commit_message:
Add subnet update BEFORE notify hook

Adding notification when subnet is being updated to allow a check
for subnet in use (as needed by VPNaaS for IPSec connections that
are using the subnet). This will be used to block the change, as
is done for deletes.

Change-Id: I33245daa158889db8a7cc9a61db8964acf5038ef
Closes-Bug: #1503862

Parameter 'amqp_durable_queues' under section 'DEFAULT' now is
deprecated since Liberty and should be placed under certain
rpc backend section [1,2]

[1] https://github.com/openstack/oslo.messaging/blob/liberty/oslo_messaging/_drivers/amqp.py#L36
[2] http://docs.openstack.org/liberty/config-reference/content/configuring-rpc.html

commit_message:
Change section name for AMQP rabbit parameters

Parameter 'amqp_durable_queues' under section 'DEFAULT' now is
deprecated since Liberty and should be placed under certain
rpc backend section [1,2]

[1] https://github.com/openstack/oslo.messaging/blob/liberty/oslo_messaging/_drivers/amqp.py#L36
[2] http://docs.openstack.org/liberty/config-reference/content/configuring-rpc.html

Change-Id: I925470be2df1983ffce4eaf5df9c1f5c48705255

commit_message:
Change section name for AMQP rabbit parameters

Parameter 'amqp_durable_queues' under section 'DEFAULT' now is
deprecated since Liberty and should be placed under certain
rpc backend section [1,2]

[1] https://github.com/openstack/oslo.messaging/blob/liberty/oslo_messaging/_drivers/amqp.py#L36
[2] http://docs.openstack.org/liberty/config-reference/content/configuring-rpc.html

Change-Id: I0d15f77e6905179398aee1d246e99f03e0796334

commit_message:
Change section name for AMQP rabbit parameters

Parameter 'amqp_durable_queues' under section 'DEFAULT' now is
deprecated since Liberty and should be placed under certain
rpc backend section [1,2]

[1] https://github.com/openstack/oslo.messaging/blob/liberty/oslo_messaging/_drivers/amqp.py#L36
[2] http://docs.openstack.org/liberty/config-reference/content/configuring-rpc.html

Change-Id: Ib7bbea586b21c42eb9fd13c4a376d23fce165272

commit_message:
Catch 3 InvalidBDM related exc when boot instance

InvalidBDMEphemeralSize ,InvalidBDMFormat and
InvalidBDMSwapSize exception might be raised during
boot process while we didn't catch this exception at API
layer so 500 will be returned. This patch makes it return
HTTPBadRequest.

Note this didn't require microversion bump per microversion
dev mentioned and legacy v2 code already have Invalid exception
catched and handled.

Change-Id: I98bd8edab3a2801c876d53c0336ea2f8da5396aa
Related-Bug: 1483645
Closes-Bug: 1504264

commit_message:
Introduce murano:config to manage custom options

This murano::config is aim to use murano config resources
to manage custom configurations in murano config files.

This will make end user easy to add their own custom options
in Hiera data.

Change-Id: I256b52ad242d99114cf41637b4ff14170d7f4595

hi terry 
i was planning on completing this work myself in this cycle.
i have been busy completing the release work for the networking-ovs-dpdk repo for liberty.

i would prefer not to take the sub classing approach.
i only did that in the networking-ovs-dpdk repo to prevent frequent breakage in the out of tree fork. i don't this is the best approach intree.

in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/197210/ we discussed 

storing the datapath_type and ovs supported interfaces types in the the agent report configurations section. 

the ovs mechanism driver will then be extended to set the vif type and populate the vif bindings by reading these values decideing vhost user is supported.

i will create a RFE bug to track this.
i had planed on submitting the code before the summit so that we could discuss and hopefully merged before mitika 1"}, {'account_id': 5756, 'date': '2015-10-14 15:01:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

sean: the ovs supported interface types is unfortunately not sufficient to determine whether or not we *should* do dpdk on a host, only that we are capable of it, correct? Even with datapath_type=netdev, that doesn't necessarily mean DPDK...just that for some reason we want to use the OVS netdev datapath.

With this solution, we have a single config option, and we can specify any number of configs. This wouldn't even really have to be subclassing the agent, it could just be some config object that gets passed.

My main goal with this implementation style was to get away from having lots of different config options, many of which might not be compatible with each other--like if some other netdev using OVS feature comes along, for example."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-15 17:44:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

Terry you're missing the Closes Bug tag. Also the automated capability detection thingie should be in a separate patch anyway IMO."}, {'account_id': 5756, 'date': '2015-10-15 23:36:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

It's easy enough to implement just as

 class BaseOVS(object):
     @property
     def config(self):               
         return self.ovsdb.db_list("Open_vSwitch").execute()[0]

Then anywhere you want to check, then:

commit_message:
Add DPDK support to OVS mech driver and agent

To merge OVS+DPDK support into the existing OVS mech driver and
agent, is useful to allow the OVS agent to pass VIF details based on
the port context up to the OVS mech driver.

This removes the config options for 'agent_type' and 'datapath_type',
and replaces it with an OVS 'agent_driver' option. This driver is
passed via the agent 'configurations' dict. The plugin can use this
information when binding ports.

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1506127
Change-Id: I29c49529e28515e85655c4dc4360ea417bde73b1

commit_message:
libvirt:on snapshot delete, use qemu-img to blockRebase if VM is stopped

Libvirt won't do a blockRebase on a domain that is not running. So,
in that case, use "qemu-img rebase" instead.

Note: For now, trying to rebase a network disk using qemu-img raises
a NovaException error because I can't test that it successfully works
for every protocol (gluster, sheepdog, etc) that executes this code
path. I successfully tested this with file-based disk.

Change-Id: I0e6819a6c8dc70b9bd7d1a9c18dc185b4537a3e4
Closes-Bug: #1444806
Closes-Bug: #1465416

Add warnings for deprecated IndirectionAPI methods

This adds some warnings and comments when we encounter unsupported
IndirectionAPI methods for manifest-based operations.

How is this patch different from having the following in the keystone policy.json (assuming policy.v3cloudsample.json is deployed)?


"cloud_admin":
    "rule:admin_required and domain_id:admin_domain_id
    or
    "rule:admin_required and project_id:admin_project_id",'}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2015-10-12 17:31:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

David:  No differnce, but what we are finding is that people are not modifying their policy.json files, and for many organizations, are not allowed to.  THus, adding the admin_domain_id into the policy cannot happen.'}, {'account_id': 11333, 'date': '2015-10-12 17:37:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: -Code-Review'}, {'account_id': 5707, 'date': '2015-10-12 18:16:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

So although this is a clever option, I'm fundamentally against us adding code to solve the fact that people are not updating their policy files.  I believe the better solution is for use to provide better examples, better documentation and work with the other projects to get the policy files corrected. I still consider the "Admin-ness not properly scoped" bug to be Invalid.'}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2015-10-12 19:05:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

@henry, we need something like this or to make v2 adhere to actual policy. I think this is a fine intermediary solution unless we have v2 also update to use policy.json (keystone issue)

The non-keystone projects needing to update policy is a valid argument. I would like to see comment from nova, cinder, etc to make sure this isnt breaking some assumption.'}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2015-10-13 03:24:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Editing the policy files is problematic in an automated install.  The ordering is very complex.  You have to create the admin domain, get the id, and then templatize all of the policy files with the automated id.  Considering that OpenStack does not have a single installer, we cannot dicatate how this is done.

Getting changes to the use of admin in policy file involves making a change to every single project that uses policy, everything under the big tent. While that is an admirable long term goal, it has not been done in several releases, and does not look like it is going to happen quickly.  This change fixes the short term issue while we work towards a longer term solution around automated policy management.'}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2015-10-13 13:32:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

I'm not convinced this actually helps much. And I'm worried that it gets things going the wrong direction and will make it harder to get a real solution developed. I'm not sure having a single top-level project is a bad thing, but stripping the "admin" role out for others... ugh!

@Morgan, why do we need a solution for v2 here? Just add this to the list of security problems with v2 and have people move to v3. We should be deprecating v2 in the next few weeks, so investing there doesn't seem to make sense. That ship has sailed.

@Henry, I don't think the bug is completely invalid. Matt, the problem is that nothing has moved on policy.  Keystone does not control the policy files of the other projects, and this issue has been out there for several years.

The bug is based on the fact that we changed roles from global to scoped.  But Admin as a role never was updated.  Until we can get this in place, we have no way to actually fix things across all the projects.'}, {'account_id': 10608, 'date': '2015-10-14 11:00:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

I do not agree that we have to put this in place to fix things across the other projects.

While I very much appreciate that this is an issue that will require changes across the big tent, that does not mean we cannot make incremental changes. The bug that is referenced in your patch is specific to keystone in its description, and can be solved specific to keystone. Start there. Then move to nova or cinder or whatever and fix things there if someone else hasn't already done that in parallel. We do not have to limit our contributions to keystone when we see an issue somewhere else. And this is more our area of expertise than theirs... they will require our help.

I've seen it said a couple times that there is no current notion of admin being scoped to a project among the other areas of the big tent, but that's actually not true:
1) nova and cinder require that an admin explicitly provide the "all_tenants" query parameter when they want to operate across projects. Otherwise things are scoped to the project from the token. This is not a full/proper solution, because an admin who does specify all_tenants can still operate across projects, and that shouldn't be possible (instead, it should be possible to scope a token to a project *and* its children projects, rather than just to a single project... something to address in keystone). But it's a partial solution.
2) ceilometer limits many of its requests to the project scoped in the token.

You're assuming the solution here demands an admin project. If it does, only keystone should care about what that is, so we should not be putting an admin project id into the policy files of nova, cinder, etc. if that's what you were suggesting. Though maybe you were just talking about a distributed keystone environment?

Let's assume we do need an admin project for the sake of keystone. This would be a special singleton project, a parent of all other domains/projects, but with its own separate identity backend so it can have distinct/separate users. When it is created, we can record its id in the db, rather than in policy. You'd have to have your token scoped to this special project only if you want to administer this special project itself, including adding new child domains/projects. If you want to add a user/role to a lower-level domain, you would just need a token scoped to that domain. We could continue to support environments that do not have this special admin project setup, though that should be deprecated.'}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2015-10-14 20:34:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Doing anything beyond this task is a multi-release effort.  There is currently no way to synchronize any of the policy information.  Adding something like an admin project, or a project that has special permissions on an endpoint, or any other tooling like that cannot be done under the current restrictions.

However, this change does not prohibit such an effort being undertaken in the future.  The Dynamic Policy effort, which has been underway for two releases now, attempts to do just that.  This fix addresses the status quo.  Synchronizing policy efforts across all of the project can happen as well.

But there is no consensus, yet, and thus, we are left with a role assignments mechanism that is neither necessary nor sufficient.  

Note that in the latest version of the patch, the single admin project has been replaced with a MultiStrOpt approach, allowing for multiple projects that can accept the admin role.'}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2015-10-14 20:35:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Commit message was updated'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-14 22:15:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified-1
