I am in support of this patch even though I may not agree with the scope (no pun intended) of the problem it is solving. Nevertheless, it is a viable solution for a real use case, which is to put a safty harness around the promiscuous "admin" role. OpenStack is about choices. As a community, we need choices. Choice is about making difficult tradeoffs, whether we like it or not. This patch may not solve all of my problems, but it doesn't mean it won't solve Adams or others problems.

Lets be clear here, this patch does not cure all our adminess ills (i.e. it does not provide service-specific admin isolation, or lack of clear separation between project and service admin in general). So its more like "Partial-Bug: 968696" then "Closes-Bug: 968696". This patch simply lock down the "admin" role to a certain extend.

As Adam mentioned earlier, this patch does not prevent us from persuing our long term goal of better role management system, better authorization APIs, and better cross-service coordination in general (which we seem to be lacking at the moment).'}, {'account_id': 10608, 'date': '2015-10-15 00:20:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

gyee is right that it would absolutely have to be considered Partial-Bug at best, not Closes-Bug, if this were to merge. I'm affected by bug 968696, but I could never use this as it would cause other problems. I need to be able to have an admin on various projects for the sake of nova, cinder, etc. I wonder if anyone could use this, really, for that reason.

I'm still very much -1 on this."}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2015-10-15 00:41:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Nova etc. either checks for Admin or a project scope.  No policy rule currently checks for both.  

Further policy work would and should be done beyond this.  It is just a fix for a very small portion of the problem, due to the fact that roles used to be global.  If it does not fix thing sfor you, it should at least not make them worse.'}, {'account_id': 10608, 'date': '2015-10-15 13:44:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

I didn't say nova, cinder, etc. were using policy to check the project. They do that in code. Which is more correct that doing it in policy... roles given to a project should only apply to that project. You shouldn't be able to override that with policy.json... that needs to be (and is in lots of places) hardcoded behavior."}, {'account_id': 6486, 'date': '2015-10-15 15:08:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

can we see this in action in devstack?'}, {'account_id': 6486, 'date': '2015-10-15 15:08:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

recheck should work now'}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2015-10-15 16:11:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Good to know that checks are scoped, but it only requires one API to not check to scope to cause a security violation.  Is Nova good across the board?  Is Cinder?'}, {'account_id': 1916, 'date': '2015-10-15 16:22:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Brant, the way it is proposed right now, making it work in devstack would be a bit clumsy. It'll be a two step bootstrapping. Perhaps insteading putting an arbitary (UUID) admin project ID and admin project domain ID in keystone.conf, we create an immutable admin project with a constant ID, the same way we bootstrap the 'Default' domain and the '__member__' role?

Matthew, doing hardcoded authorization check is not preferable because

1. it would be hard to audit the permissions and generate an audit report without also having the read-the-fantastical-code. :)
2. it is already bad enough that Horizon have to import and parse each service static policy.json file in order to setup an intuitive UI (i.e. hide/grey-out the menu items that user have no access to). Now ask them to also parse the source code.
3. I can't imagine the number of false positives a static code auditing tools such as bandit may be generating.

Instead, lets think what we can do in both short and long term. This patch doesn't change what we need to do long term."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-15 16:31:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

@ayoung, whether nova/cinder/etc. are doing this perfectly today is not the right question. They're attempting to do it correctly. If they have a bug, that is their bug. We cannot afford to be overprotective here. They will not appreciate it (keep reading). Let them be big boys and take responsibility for their own security issues.

This hack may work for someone who is only using keystone, but its design is keystone-centric and it will not work for folks using nova, cinder, etc. They are counting on having an admin role on EVERY project. Stripping it off like this does is not going to work with their policy.json files. Things which require the admin role will simply stop working for any project not marked as an admin project. Since these things need to work, you'll have to mark every project an admin project... in which case you'd be back to where you were before this patch.

@gyee nobody needs to parse the source code here. I don't understand why you think that would be needed by auditing or horizon or anything else. It's simple... you're only allowed to take actions on the project for which your token is scoped. Period. End of story. That is a simple rule for Horizon, etc. to understand/expect. There is no need to read code to learn that."}, {'account_id': 1916, 'date': '2015-10-15 23:47:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Matthew, I was responding to your comment on Patch Set 5.

Regarding to Horizon, its not that simple. It still needs to find out what the given token can do. Scoping and (role and attribute based) access control are two different things. Scoping is about *what resources that are visible to you* and access control is *what you can do, or what actions can you perform, to those resources*. Scope should not imply all access. Policies give us the ability to control who (based on token) can perform which action (CRUD) to which resource (i.e. server, network, etc). For example, suppose we want a reader/observer role that has read-only access to the resources for a given project for support purposes, how would that be possible with hardcoded checks? Adding new code every time we update a role?'}, {'account_id': 10608, 'date': '2015-10-16 00:15:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

@gyee Yes to everything you said in your last comment. None of that has anything to do with this, though. I'm not suggesting hardcoded checks for policy. The issue here is scoping."}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2015-10-16 02:18:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Gyee, Matthew is right that scoping should be checked by code, and not policy.  Scoping is an engineering effort, and should not be modified on a final deployment.  The only value that should be configurable foe policy is the role required to perform the role.

This change actually facilitates getting ther, by "grandfathering in" the admin role.  It essentially removes the need to do the scope check for admin;  the projects are already not doing a scope check for admin anyway, and this just protects against that.'}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2015-10-16 02:19:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Matt:  can you provide some example APIs of where the admin role is expected to be on a project?'}, {'account_id': 5707, 'date': '2015-10-16 10:26:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

So a couple of things:

1) The amount of discussion this is generating clear indicates that git review comments is not the appropriate mechanism.  There needs to be a spec for this change that can be discussed.

2) The keystone cloud sample policy file DOES scope the role to the project, so it's not true to say that nobody does this - and there is no reason why other os projects could not use the same principle. (As an aside I'm supportive of moving *where* to look for scope out of policy into code, but not that fact that you want to use scope)

3) I *think* there are two issues that 2) above can not solve:
a) Keystone v2 API does not use the policy file to check it's own API (this was introduced in v3)
b) Any hard-coded checks in other os projects that don't use policy

So as a move to "fix" keystone v2 APIs I'd be OK with this, provided the config value was marked as deprecated at the same time as the v2 API.'}, {'account_id': 10608, 'date': '2015-10-16 11:10:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

When creating the RequestContext in nova (nova/context.py), the is_admin flag is set based on a policy check for the "context_is_admin" policy setting. The default value for that policy setting in nova's policy.json is "role:admin". So all the policies for which you see "rule:admin_api" (which rule is defined as "is_admin:True" in default policy) are tied to tokens with the admin role or cases where the context is elevated. Some of those checks are really only for elevated context cases, I'm sure, but many are not. You can find a host of API examples based on that. One would be PUT /v2.1/{tenant_id}/os-quota-sets (updating quotas for a tenant/project).

This patch doesn't just remove the need to do scope checks for admin. I understand that was the intent, but it goes far beyond that. It removes the ability to do checks for the admin role when the request is scoped to a tenant/project that is not marked as an admin project, breaking all those nova APIs that are currently only allowed for admins.'}, {'account_id': 1916, 'date': '2015-10-16 22:12:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Sure bp/spec sound reasonable. Lets talk it over in Tokyo.

++ on v2 deprecation and work on elevating cloud admin policy as default.

On the service side, we really don't have a good anyway to distinguish project admin, service admin, domain admin, and cloud admin right now. That's disturbing.

Scope evaluation is tightly coupled with search queries anyway so doing it at the policy level may not be very efficient right now. But typically, if we truly want to support fine-grained access control, a role should be corresponding to a set of operations/actions on a set of resources at the atomic level."}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2015-10-17 00:57:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

This was my previous effort along these lines.  I think it is probably more what you are thinking of.

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/228477/2/specs/backlog/catalog-roles.rst,cm

In short, a user would get a role on an item in the service catalog.

This is not a magic bullet:  1) the fact that a role assignment is scoped to an endpoint still needs to be communicated from Keystone to endpoint. 2) The  Horizon UI needs to continue to work.  3) We need to separate normal projects from endpoints.

admin as something that can only be exposed for endpoint scoped operations still maps better to previous policy implementations.

If what you say about Nova policy now is true, then Nova policy is already broken;  admin anywhere is admin everywhere already.'}, {'account_id': 11333, 'date': '2015-10-20 17:54:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

This patch if enabled does more than what cloud_admin rule does.  A user with admin role, but not in the admin project or domain basically gets admin role stripped, thus no is_admin capability in any services.  This is more than keeping which admin is the keystone admin like cloud_admin rule does.  Is this the intend or a side-effect?
If I understand the patch correctly, an alternative is manually removing admin role from users that donât belong to admin project or admin domain produce end result.'}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2015-10-28 05:10:40.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

The Admin project needs to be added to the  data used for policy enforcement.  Just excluding projects will not work with existing APIs'}]

commit_message:
Strip admin roles from non-admin projects and domains

Adds two new configuration values:

admin_project_id
admin_domain_id

Each of these are MultiStrOpts, meaning they can take multiple
values.

If admin_project_id is set, only projects that match the
admin_project_id will effectively have the admin role.
Tokens requested for projects other than this will have
the admin role stripped out.

admin_domain_id works the same for domain scoped tokens.

Change-Id: Iac82505ac210e9939fdaa05a5c0f78c9c9475bf9
closes-bug: 968696

commit_message:
Make ConsoleauthTestCase inherit from NoDBTest

ConsoleauthTestCase only create instance but it can be
mocked because not actually used. This patch remove
those reference by a fake instance uuid and make
ConsoleauthTestCase inherit from NoDBTest.

Change-Id: Ib58c5bf4d61de41aa9f5ac995a19bc8b26e88e62

commit_message:
test_snapshot_pattern: cleanup class scope variable usage

This removes the class variables for keypair and security group
so we don't rely on tight coupling between method calls.

Change-Id: I0888aae97ab134601fae824d7af017da4318d669
Related-Bug: #1482299

commit_message:
Add missing cgsnapshot field to Snapshot object

SQLAlchemy model of snapshot specifies its relationship to cgsnapshot.
This wasn't reflected in Snapshot versioned object. The patch adds
cgsnapshot field to Snapshot object as well as required unit tests.

Partial-Bug: 1509012
Change-Id: I285930222c491f83a35fdef78067e9548e4b845a

commit_message:
make grenade multinode run more places

We should make grenade multinode run on every grenade change in a
non-voting way to get this into a stable state.

Add to Nova experimental as well to be able to test changes to fix
things from there.

Change-Id: I9f42051ad3bfee338e581be527a7eb13f3ff4aa3

commit_message:
Log the exception in linuxbridge_neutron_agent as exception

The log here should be logged as exception. 1) It is more readable.
2) It keeps consistent with the action of its sibling module,
ovs_neutron_agent.

Change-Id: Idf11a617369cbee0dc23c8e56ae9475bb41dcc02
Closes-bug: #1508270

[{'created': '2015-10-23 00:32:33.000000000', 'message': 'SLO docs(tring): manifest params in table, code block; copyedits

It's Ã¦sthetically pleasing to display the segment description parameters
in a table (using the reStructuredText "simple" table markup) and to use
a code block (which receives syntax hightlighting in the rendered
document!) for the example JSON fragment. Also, a few very minor copy
changes are made (a comma after an introductory phrase clarifies; JSON
and ETag receieve their canonical capitalizations; the elements of the
manifest JSON aren't "files" exactly; the inclusive nature of the range
is noted for the benefit of harried readers who won't read the "Range
Specification" section later in the document).

Change-Id: I5296fc04c6fe5410ad14bba7de0a7f8ab060b126
'}]
commit_message:
SLO docs(tring): manifest params in table, code block; copyedits

It's Ã¦sthetically pleasing to display the segment description parameters
in a table (using the reStructuredText "simple" table markup) and to use
a code block (which receives syntax hightlighting in the rendered
document!) for the example JSON fragment. Also, a few very minor copy
changes are made (a comma after an introductory phrase clarifies; JSON
and ETag receieve their canonical capitalizations; the elements of the
manifest JSON aren't "files" exactly; the inclusive nature of the range
is noted for the benefit of harried readers who won't read the "Range
Specification" section later in the document).

Change-Id: I5296fc04c6fe5410ad14bba7de0a7f8ab060b126

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

Add Magnum Atomic image to glance

This commit adds a link for the Fedora Atomic
image used with OpenStack Magnum
(https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Magnum)

commit_message:
Replace utils.exec for IpNeighComm LinuxBridge drv

Replace all execution of "ip neigh" command using
utils.exec for ip_lib.IpNeighCommand.(add,delete)
in LinuxBridge driver

Changed multiple which for one and fixed indentations
Closes-Bug: #1311019

Change-Id: I1389941b7df11c089429f1de61eac6d7ea5d0e54

commit_message:
Namespace XTRACE calls

As a follow-on to Iba7739eada5711d9c269cb4127fa712e9f961695 in
devstack, where we rename the XTRACE storage calls to not conflict, do
the same in grenade

Also some minor turning-down of tracing when importing stackrc; it
floods the logs with irrelevant stuff.  And now we're tracing
properly, cleanup "echo_summary" output in the logs.

Change-Id: Ibb67a6454e4465a8d0493461e32dbae96c6a03e7

commit_message:
Includes server_default option in is_domain column

is_domain field in project table does not have the server_default
parameter set. We set it as '0' to comply with migration's default.

Co-Authored-By: Henrique Truta <henrique@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>

Change-Id: Ida6a43ca9b61771f4366e900a46f62cda87f8f27

commit_message:
Adds availability zone real data model spec

The availability zones API calls in Nova are incorrect and confusing.
This spec describes a possible enhancement for how to store and display
information about availability zones across a deployment.

Change-Id: If473431179f225a15cb7b975deab6b70a25f37b5
Blueprint: availability-zone-real-data-model

There are several TODOs like:
https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/api/openstack/compute/quota_sets.py#L157

I think return 200 and 204 means different to user who really pay attention to async and sync success
and it would be better for us to follow the http spec as much as we can ... thanks'}, {'account_id': 5754, 'date': '2015-10-08 13:16:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Emm...same concern with Michael.  We said we won't change something just for consistent. 200->202 is pretty useful. for 200->201 actually not get enough benefit. But let me put this in next api meeting agenda, let's get agreement on this.

Hold -1 after api meeting discussion."}, {'account_id': 5754, 'date': '2015-10-08 13:19:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Make nova auto-select RPC versions

This leverages Nova's new ability to auto-select the compute rpc version.

commit_message:
Expands python34 unit tests list

Commit Ibe5ecde51655334adafba12280a44d2ddd22c7ec introduced some
python 3.4 compatible changes that were not tested by gate-nova-python34.

Removes unit tests from tests-py3.txt blacklist that covers the changes
made in the mentioned commit.

Adds fixes in order for newly enabled unit tests to pass.

Partially implements blueprint: nova-python3-mitaka

Change-Id: Id1268b53e68edf375e852d33d028e2da57e69bad

commit_message:
Fix test_show_default_quota_set_xxx

There is an internal test method _test_show_default_quota_set, but
the method is not used for test_show_default_quota_set_xxx.
That means show_default_quota_set() is not tested on unit tests.
This patch makes test_show_default_quota_set_xxx use the internal
method for the unit test purpose.

Change-Id: Id0322784f42c5380dc887d1fbd844cf8a3482cf6

commit_message:
Add multi-initiator extra-spec for Nimble driver

This patch allows setting up multi-initiator access for
the Nimble driver through the extra-specs.

This can be set by adding the key 'nimble:multi-initiator'
with boolean value of 'true' or 'false'. If nothing is
specified it defaults to 'false'.

Change-Id: Iade49f0ce418a2db7ea9a00ebf925a017e3eb429
Closes-Bug: #1495750

commit_message:
Delegate log formatting to logging package

We should delegate (when possible) formatting to the logger in order to
perform formatting only when needed, by using:

 LOG.<level>(message, data)

instead of:

 LOG.<level>(message % data)

Change-Id: I55a949a3908eaef5757815d735de4320645e9764

commit_message:
[install] Liberty updates for neutron

More neutron configuration updates for Liberty including
some changes for RDO packages.

1) Remove explicit configuration of kernel parameters
   because neutron handles them.
2) Explicitly add DNS resolver to virtual networks
   because default value prevents name resolution within
   instances.
3) Move some configuration options to better locations.
4) RDO: Remove workaround for init scripts.
5) RDO: Explicitly configure lock_path in neutron.conf file.
6) RDO: Install openstack-neutron package on compute nodes
   because it also installs packages on which the Linux
   bridge agent depends.

Change-Id: I2c70c64e1272ee33eb364c079d8187ade7235ee2
Implements: blueprint installguide-liberty

commit_message:
devstack: enable cloudkitty services by default

Users using the cloudkitty devstack plugin want to use cloudkitty.
Because of that it makes no sense to not enable the cloudkitty services
provided by this devstack plugin by default.

Change-Id: I7188397233bcc43df39a66d407d92f6a844f374c

commit_message:
Change in sort direction at execution controller

API sort workflow execution by default using 'created_at'
and descending direction, which should be ascending.

Change-Id: I5405b73c9ca95b16ce0aacd76ad8134a6474ce33
Closes-Bug:#1510417

commit_message:
test_backup_nfs: Set volume id per test

Since some of these tests trigger operations (such as
progress reporting) that can happen as an asyncronous
task, set a different ID for each test so it's possible
to identify where notifications are coming from.

Related-Bug: #1501745

Change-Id: I4cb3400d302f03d19d982979bc5f3c3b90eb47a4

commit_message:
Fix node arch and install Guide links in HA Guide Hardware setup

The 'neutron' and 'nova-network' links point to the Kilo version of the
Install Guide, as the hardware setup is based around that 3-node
architecture.
The Liberty Install Guide now uses a 2-node architecture. The HA Guide
should be updated to reflect this 2-node architecture, and these two
links should be updated to the Liberty Install Guide.

Change-Id: I36a0fd0605ee9c8837c1f66318550e82c3f74fa2
Closes-bug: #1506374

commit_message:
Enable encryption for all RabbitMQ connections

This change enables encryption between OpenStack services and RabbitMQ by
default.

Closes-bug: 1509086

Change-Id: Ic95a556e001f66df935ea7db613b497b47062851
(cherry picked from commit d930a7b55c6e5e96f9da07669a243a30b6a9432e)

commit_message:
Use LOG.error when no exception handler is used

There's no need to use LOG.exception here since sys.exc_info()
results in (None, None, None) and thus would effectively just
be LOG.error.

Also, the failure of invoking LOG.exception outside of an
exception handler is due to a bug in Python3[1]. The fix for
that is only available in Python3.5.

[1] http://bugs.python.org/issue17911

Closes-Bug: #1482261

Change-Id: I9ceac0fceafa45769cc15f56027c981182ff0750
(cherry picked from commit f5c415accfff2ad399194b30b9408a903042f009)

commit_message:
Improve unit test coverage for alt_auth data

Using alternative or empty auth_data is only tested for one
of the auth parts. Extend tests to cover headers, body and url.

commit_message:
Remove references to Swift in chunked driver

After the chunked/Swift backup driver refactor in commit
2f701a39208f9396893cd8a57165e37cfeb6fc2f
some references to 'Swift' remained in code comments and
log messages in code that no longer lives in the Swift driver
proper.

This commit cleans up those leftovers.

Change-Id: I9c83661ed380cf728c9262d39f89cce0bc341509
Closes-Bug: 1452864

commit_message:
Adding ability to register image without description

set_description method of SaharaImageManager was changed
so that its description parameter became optional

Change-Id: Ib357872e658b9c74f12cfedc1b505ce00e555d0f
Closes-bug: #1510505

Thanks for submitting this change - I have a couple of comments:

You can't just change the names of the CONF settings. The old names need to be marked as deprecated using the deprecate_name option. You can see how to use this by searching in cfg.py for the deprecated_name keyworkd.. The trove project is attempting to follow the OpenStack standard deprecation guidelines described here [1]. That document should provide some background as to why this is important. 

You should put more detail in your commit message; I shouldn't have to look at the bug report to get a high level understanding of why this change is being made.

commit_message:
Changes names of some quota values

Some variables which were actually per-tenant were
incorrectly named with a _user. Corrected this
confusion by making the old names deprecated
and providing new per-tenant names.

Closes Bug: #1232969

Change-Id: I541ed990c0cdd40b3805d2e2a166363d9ff2ad04

commit_message:
Check dashboard symlinks during horizon plugin installation

This patch add '-f' flag to horizon plugin symlink generation.
It helps to prevent deployment fails if symlink already exists.

Change-Id: I94ece2689c9b7332958e32788b5531d540b063f8
Closes-Bug: #1508023
(cherry picked from commit 0ced0071095248283ec4f95aadeaea962e096fa9)

Updating keystone auth for Rally tests

Adding support for Keystone v2/v3 auth.
generate_random_name now part of rally.common.utils

commit_message:
Enable encryption for all RabbitMQ connections

This change enables encryption between OpenStack services and RabbitMQ by
default.

Closes-bug: 1509086

Change-Id: Ic95a556e001f66df935ea7db613b497b47062851

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 9003, 'date': '2015-10-02 00:27:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 12: Code-Review-1

Well, it's not true that:

val / 1024 / 1024 / 2 is the same as val / (1024 / 1024 / 2)

On the left hand side, val is divided by 1024, then reduced further on each subsequent divide.

On the right hand side, val is divided by one half (1024/1024) = 1, which is then divided by 2.

To me this just underscores the fact that while the code is pretty clear - the constant should be expressed as a product - the commit message is still confusing.  It probably captures the mental process behind the original mistake, thinking in terms of divides and not grouping the operands properly for the order of evaluation - but it leaves much to be desired in terms of a simple, clear explanation of the fix.

I think it should just say that the correct method is to divide by the constant, where the constant is expressed by the product that appears in the code."}, {'account_id': 13203, 'date': '2015-10-03 03:06:18.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 13.'}, {'account_id': 13203, 'date': '2015-10-03 03:11:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 13:

'}, {'created': '2015-09-23 02:58:18.000000000', 'message': "Fix capacity report error in Huawei driver

Currently the capacity report is incorrect due
to the way the capacity report is currently
being calculated. This patch will fix it.

In drivers/huawei/rest_client.py, we calculate
the capacity like this:
free = float(pool_info['CAPACITY']) / constants.CAPACITY_UNIT

The right calculate method should be:
free = float(pool_info['CAPACITY']) / 1024.0 / 1024.0 / 2
If CAPACITY_UNIT = 1024.0 / 1024.0 / 2, finally the result is:
free = float(pool_info['CAPACITY']) / (1024.0 / 1024.0 / 2)
This is incorrect.

Closes-Bug: #1498452
Change-Id: I4dc20ef8805d7c414fedb1dc441deb3f9fcd75b5

"}, {'created': '2015-10-01 12:51:50.000000000', 'message': "Fix capacity report error in Huawei driver

Currently the capacity report is incorrect due
to the way the capacity report is currently
being calculated. This patch will fix it.

In drivers/huawei/rest_client.py, we calculate
the capacity like this:
free = float(pool_info['CAPACITY']) / constants.CAPACITY_UNIT

The right calculate method should be:
free = float(pool_info['CAPACITY']) / 1024.0 / 1024.0 / 2
If CAPACITY_UNIT = 1024.0 / 1024.0 / 2, finally the result is:
free = float(pool_info['CAPACITY']) / (1024.0 / 1024.0 / 2)
This is equal to:
free = float(pool_info['CAPACITY']) / 1024.0 * 1024.0 * 2
And this is incorrect.

Closes-Bug: #1498452
Change-Id: I4dc20ef8805d7c414fedb1dc441deb3f9fcd75b5
"}, {'created': '2015-10-03 03:06:18.000000000', 'message': "Fix capacity report error in Huawei driver

Currently the capacity report is incorrect due
to wrong way code clear.

The previous right way is:
result = var / 1024.0 / 1024.0 / 2

We use a constant CAPACITY_UNIT to make the code cleaner
like this:
CAPACITY_UNIT = 1024.0 / 1024.0 / 2
result = var / CAPACITY_UNIT

We want the CAPACITY_UNIT work like a *real* constant like C
language, but in python, it is not a *real* constant, it's
just a variable. It will calculate the CAPACITY_UNIT first,
so the finally result is:
result = var / 0.5

This patch will fix this.

Closes-Bug: #1498452
Change-Id: I4dc20ef8805d7c414fedb1dc441deb3f9fcd75b5

like this:
CAPACITY_UNIT = 1024.0 / 1024.0 / 2
result = var / CAPACITY_UNIT
We want the CAPACITY_UNIT work like a *real* constant like C
language, but in python, it is not a *real* constant, it's
just a variable. It will calculate the CAPACITY_UNIT first,
so the finally result is:
result = var / 0.5
And this is wrong.

This patch will fix this.

Closes-Bug: #1498452
Change-Id: I4dc20ef8805d7c414fedb1dc441deb3f9fcd75b5
"}]
commit_message:
Fix capacity report error in Huawei driver

Currently the capacity report is incorrect due
to wrong way code clear.

The previously right way is:
result = var / 1024.0 / 1024.0 / 2

But currently we use a constant CAPACITY_UNIT to make the code cleaner
like this:
CAPACITY_UNIT = 1024.0 / 1024.0 / 2
result = var / CAPACITY_UNIT
We want the CAPACITY_UNIT work like a *real* constant like C
language, but in python, it is not a *real* constant, it's
just a variable. It will calculate the CAPACITY_UNIT first,
so the finally result is:
result = var / 0.5
And this is wrong.

This patch will fix this.

Closes-Bug: #1498452
Change-Id: I4dc20ef8805d7c414fedb1dc441deb3f9fcd75b5

+2 this, but I'm not entirely sure this change is actually doing what was intended (or I'm misreading what the intention is).  If I set lxc_cache_resolvers, my containers get the specified resolvers in /etc/resolv.conf but the first entry is always the IP of the dnsmasq running on the host.  This means that the DNS resolvers I specified are not used, unless of course the dnsmasq on the host dies or something to that effect.  Was that the desired result?  Perhaps we need to update the dhclient.conf in the container to not request domain-name-servers when lxc_cache_resolvers is set?"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-26 15:12:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

@Matt you are correct that this does set the DNS resolvers to whatever the user adds to the list, with by default is 8.8.8.8 and 8.8.4.4. As you've pointed out when the container is running the address of the host is used however Where this is most effective is when updating the container cache and interacting with the container image directly which happens from within a chroot and is not under a normal LXC running process. Our base image uses 69.20.0.164 and 69.20.0.196 for DNS which may or may not be resolvable from within the deployers target hosts and should they not work a deployer would not be able to continue a normal deployment. To ensure a deployer is able to set the DNS within the container this PR injects known resolvers into the image."}, {'account_id': 7307, 'date': '2015-10-27 10:30:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

OK, that makes sense Kevin!  I was wondering why you were updating /run/resolvconf/resolv.conf inside the container, but this explains it.  I'm assuming doing that means you do not need to run resolvconf -u?

On a side note -- do you think we need to do additional work (in a separate patch) to get containers to use the specified resolvers _only_ when they come up?

I'm going to +1 as this seems more applicable for a backport to a stable branch, but I'd love to hear what others think about backporting this."}, {'account_id': 7217, 'date': '2015-10-27 10:39:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-27 10:39:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

commit_message:
Make the container cache resolvers configurable

This change simply makes it possible for a deployer to change
the in container resolvers.

In the bootstrap-aio script the resolvers are being set in the
user_variables so containers are using the same resolvers as the
host.

Change-Id: Id7ab3632217c3eb2217a308d7226736a67900da5
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>
(cherry picked from commit 8d51f7bafc38f69c493d8573b86ed8a0f629c463)

commit_message:
Fix getting first/second ctrls in the test 'ha_neutron_destructive'

- use the list of non-primary devops nodes instead of getting
  controllers inside the loop;
- use self.show_step() for monitor steps position in logs

Change-Id: I9d81cf9479a862f167059580f2e6a8431835e48e
Closes-Bug:#1509286

commit_message:
update ceilometer verify page

Since liberty release, image.update and image.upload meters are no
longer enabled by default, so we should update the verify page to
reflect such change, otherwise user might get confused.

Change-Id: I2a6aad00ac19080fdc4eb67bbf6e62a5a1729476
Closes-Bug: #1510644

commit_message:
Add MONASCA_BASE var to DevStack plugin

Allow monasca-api to be run in both devtack and devstack-gate envs.
Use $BASE to detect which env monasca-api is running in.

Ensure that maven3 is installed.

Change-Id: I8b7748e4eacdf4aafcfebbfb6575845b9b8cade9

commit_message:
Adding interface type to client object

  This fix will allow us to pass 'os_interface' as an env variable
or as a commandline argument based on which the appropriate cue
endpoint will be used.If its not passed by default public endpoint
will be used.

Change-Id: I9c886304799a63926812f8f678016fcc0775cfa7

Change-Id: I1b084a3fee91d73d57a6b9e6a2d0ab9c186e5572

commit_message:
Use assertDictEqual to test dict equality

Just using equals is not a consistent test, because dict ordering can
change. assertDictEqual tests that the contents of the two dicts are the
same.

Change-Id: I1b084a3fee91d73d57a6b9e6a2d0ab9c186e5572

commit_message:
Update reference for rpc-maas repo

In preparation for a 10.1.16 release the rpc-maas dependency is
updated to include two fixes which update custom plugin monitors
to not use a legacy format.

commit_message:
Fix node group name when deleting a node

A wrong resource group name was used when deleting a node.
This regression was intruduced recently with Tuskar bits removal.

Change-Id: Ib8652cf70f337b2498686d583779112a329e8ac8
Closes-Bug: #1508837

commit_message:
Parse Sample volume as float

Explicitly parses sample volume as float to
prevent incorrect sample from being generated.
In case of an sample with wrong volume type,
an exception is logged.

Change-Id: I984937423fb9855d670185a1993f73d9892bfeac
Closes-Bug: #1508220

commit_message:
Test_backup_swift: Don't leak notifications

At least some of these tests can leak notifications
such as backup.createprogress.

Mock the send notification methods to ensure this
doesn't happen.

This likely indicates that some restructuring of these
tests is needed, but patching this long-standing issue
on its own is worthwhile.

Partial-Bug: #1501745

Change-Id: I91cb3bef18a8b830fcc3b3589afe6b6975bc0c2b

commit_message:
Add theme fix for browsable source code

This adds a fix to ensure that the published docs have the correct
link to the browsable source code as implemented in
https://review.openstack.org/236091

It also updates the requirements for the docs jobs to ensure
that they are in line with upstream.

Change-Id: Ic8164fd96c4ca9d286f22e7a73c84da35d16228b

commit_message:
Disable dhcp_nowait and fail on DHCP if none detected

dhcp_nowait was removed a long time ago from L23network
puppet module, so it cannot be used as an option for enabling
DHCP when there are no available DHCP servers. Since we are
checking for the presence of DHCP servers, we should fail to
apply configuration instead of waiting for Puppet to fail.

Change-Id: Ia8275d32b13a22d56922cd4a6fd6528bb7c77692

commit_message:
Set correct var for Fuel release in dockerctl

The wrong variable was in the template leaving the
version defaulted to "", and then reverting to 8.0
as hardocded by the RPM. Switched to @release var
name.

Fixed varname for dockerctl config in hardcoded conf
distributed in the RPM so it does not get replaced.

Change-Id: Ic08f92420c230aadab2c89d1abe2f03b78f4f050
Related-Commit: I28032852517ec8f7e959ad48a04621ec3e33fea1
Related-Bug: #1501368

commit_message:
Add insecure option for swift backup

When running backups with the swift backup driver and an
https url for the swift endpoint, the config option
backup_swift_ca_cert_file must point to a valid server side
cert.

For test purposes, it is useful to be able to ignore
cert errors while still making a SSL/TLS connection, the way
one can with https:// urls and the curl command and the
swift client itself.

This commit adds a boolean CONFIG option, 'backup_swift_auth_insecure',
whose default value is False, in which case there is no change from
current behavior.  If this option is set to True, however, cert validation
is skipped for SSL/TLS.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I1ca88d8e083d95c2bdb86ae79a4d66e04f521ddb

commit_message:
Fix argument order in assertEqual to (expect, obs)

assertEqual expects that the arguments provided to it should be
(expected, observed). If a particular order is kept as a convention,
then it helps to provide a cleaner message to the developer if Unit Tests
fail. There are several Unit Test files where the arguments for assertEqual
have been swapped.

Change-Id: Idf99e2b43dad5ae2b7a0ed17ea6776253f823282
Related-Bug: #1259292

commit_message:
Prevent errors due to non-existing console.html

Grep and stat were producing the error "No such file or directory"
while the consoleLog was not available to download. Keeping an empty
/tmp/console.html resolves the problem. It's also possible to debug any
possible issues with curl and grep independently since curl would
report 404 for missing url and a new error message was introduced
for missing UUID after the max retries.

Change-Id: Icb28bfca96e5eaff725d2efcfb47c3399e3991c4

Check nova v2.2 in gates

V2.2 microversion extends keypairs in Nova. This patch check that this
microversion works.

Change-Id: Ifaa7826f100bb918f53a7cac451ba577d3d29b69

Use assertIsNone instead of assertEqual(None, ***)

Instead of using assertEqual(None, ***), developers should
use assertIsNone(***).

commit_message:
Port v1.test_registry_api to Python 3

* urlsafe_b64decode(): on Python 3, decode from ASCII to get Unicode
  string.
* urlsafe_decrypt(): encode Unicode to UTF-8.
* in some loops, copy dictionary keys or items because the dictionary
  is modified in the loop body.
* test_api: use byte string for image content, not Unicode
* test_registry_api: HTTP body type is bytes, use byte strings and
  jsonutils.dump_as_bytes(), instead of native strings and
  jsonutils.dumps()
* tox.ini: add glance.tests.unit.v1.test_registry_api to Python 3.4

Change-Id: Ib9d18dce6e5728b9adf094b5aae64a86a3fea71a

Tests should use:
  self.assertIn(value, list)
  self.assertNotIn(value, list)

instead of:
  self.assertTrue(value in list)
  self.assertFalse(value in list)

because assertIn and assertNotIn raise more meaningful errors:
  self.assertIn(3, [1, 2]
  >>> MismatchError: 3 not in [1, 2]

  self.assertTrue(3 in [1, 2])
  >>> AssertionError: False is not true

commit_message:
Use assertIn and assertNotIn

Tests should use:
  self.assertIn(value, list)
  self.assertNotIn(value, list)

instead of:
  self.assertTrue(value in list)
  self.assertFalse(value in list)

because assertIn and assertNotIn raise more meaningful errors:
  self.assertIn(3, [1, 2]
  >>> MismatchError: 3 not in [1, 2]

  self.assertTrue(3 in [1, 2])
  >>> AssertionError: False is not true

Change-Id: I4b24b6e00bf26c0a68a9d8f9eb9185c435791dfc
Closes-Bug: #1510007

commit_message:
The verbose option in section [DEFAULT] has been deprecated

For more details about why this was done (by the oslo log team), see
references provided below. The change here just removes the entry from
the test config file to avoid the error.

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/206437/3

Change-Id: I941ef163561b80539397788b65aae7d4548bac49
Closes-Bug: #1507217

commit_message:
Add descriptions of response parameters for "GET /v3/roles"

Add descriptions of response parameters for "List roles" API.

For details, please see http://developer.openstack.org/api-ref-identity-v3.html#listRoles.

(df) Added missing update role and show role details calls.

Change-Id: Ic600f56efeb4532d272b45377545b65192934a16
Closes-Bug: #1510040

commit_message:
Port targets test_iet_driver to Python 3

* Replace StandardError with MemoryError: StandardError was removed
  in Python 3
* Replace __builtin__ with six.moves.builtins to mock open()
* Mock the logger in test_create_iscsi_target() because the test
  injects errors in open() and the logger uses open() to format the
  traceback
* tox.ini: add cinder.tests.unit.targets.test_iet_driver to Python 3.4

Partial-Implements: blueprint cinder-python3
Change-Id: I7c83da7374ef78cc98bd6c0c5596b7a7adb70303

commit_message:
Add base yaml support for input_data

All services continue using json-scheme.

We are going to implement mkbootstrap module for fa. In work-flow of
Fuel-Master installation, we create astute.yaml file, which should
contain user-defined ubuntu-mirrors. To reduce fuel-configuration
file i propose to fetch configs needed for bootstrapping FM in less
as possible places .

Implements: blueprint dynamically-build-bootstrap
Change-Id: Ief1d14156f6a74d1c765e9eb01c7ddb7b45a2092

Move cfapi opts to global variables view

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-26 12:07:22.000000000', 'message': "Fix endpoint type for swift dispersion

We are using service endpoint which is internal url
and set 'publicUrl' as endpoint type by default in dispersion.conf.
That's why command swift-dispersion-populate can fail.
Set endpoint type to internalUrl as it should be.

Change-Id: I2b665acd5302e6170e2a42d715f30481232e1404
Closes-bug: #1507946
"}, {'created': '2015-10-26 14:58:07.000000000', 'message': 'Fix resource ordering for swift dispersion

We should run swift dispersion only when
all other swift service are running

Closes-bug: #1507946

Change-Id: I2b665acd5302e6170e2a42d715f30481232e1404
'}, {'created': '2015-10-26 18:58:19.000000000', 'message': 'Fix resource ordering for swift dispersion

We should run swift dispersion only when
all other swift services are running

Closes-bug: #1507946

Change-Id: I2b665acd5302e6170e2a42d715f30481232e1404
'}]
commit_message:
Fix resource ordering for swift dispersion

We should run swift dispersion only when
all other swift services are running

Closes-bug: #1507946

Change-Id: I2b665acd5302e6170e2a42d715f30481232e1404

commit_message:
Resource.has_interface check get_resource_info result

This changes the behaviour of has_interface to not assume that
get_resource_info always returns a type. There are circumstances when it
won't, such as when the type is no longer in the new registry during a
stack update.

Change-Id: Idd9dade85d105dc6839ff0740e6c80aca6b7ad9f
Closes-Bug: #1509880

commit_message:
Add new context plugin to support different API versions

Services context plugin allows to path API version to clients
and service name to validate if service is available.

Co-Authored-By: Andrey Kurilin <andr.kurilin@gmail.com>

Related blueprint: different-api-versions
Change-Id: Iebc9bef0797c4afcdc8758e7819eeff43b92bf0f

commit_message:
Use kernel build-in openVswitch module for CentOS7/RHEL7

* Move hardcoded CentOS6 ovs_datapath_package_name from l23network::params.pp
to top netconfig.pp manifest.
* Add the possibility to use DKMS datapath openVswitch or kernel build-in module
for l23network.

Change-Id: I7b006a9dc3b3ec5b22dd41cc15b57d5730e4810c
Closes-bug: #1508515

commit_message:
Added config option graceful_shutdown_timeout

Option graceful_shutdown_timeout is responsible for interruption of
graceful shutdown if graceful_shutdown_timeout is exceeded.

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1446583

Change-Id: I0dfbf2d0a4943337da24c0904a1ed6f0cdccd77b

Use 'restart' instead of 'start' to apply changes

httpd is already started, so we need to use 'restart' to apply
our changes to the configuration

commit_message:
Turn the baremetal client reference into a property

Use a property instead of a function. This is more in line with how the
clients are referenced with openstackclient, thereby making it easier
to switch to the Ironic OSC plugin in the future.

Change-Id: I0b4d35f0af6136dd1bce6c6d4202caa52f4c042e

commit_message:
Fix sudoers requiretty config

TTY requirement should be disabled for sudo inside
containers since they run without a TTY in most cases.

Change-Id: Ie97f3af3a658f1d8244068d425dc9a6319e75823
Closes-Bug: #1510031

This is just showing a copy of the url, because it is based on request.path instead of subfolders. It makes sense to have this as an independent patch, but consider whether to merge until the follow-on patch is done to show names instead of ids. The object ids are disconcerting to all but experts; and besides, I can already see the URL.

Some of the object ids crash when you click on them. For example, drill down into network and then into a subnet. Click the network's id, and it gives a Page Not Found. Same thing with Access & Security, and others.

No breadcrumb for Network Topo?"}, {'account_id': 9576, 'date': '2014-10-23 02:26:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

@Randy, I did a bit of investigation into remapping id to name. As you probably notice from the patch, there are four main views: modal, workflow, tables and tabs. Of those, only modal and workflow have a get_object_id and get_object_name method. These two methods take in a parameter, the resource API object. For tables and tabs, it looks like one can access it via the get_data method. As you know, the resource object are fetched via API calls to various services, they can be expensive to perform, but lucky for us, some of it is cache temporarily.

Well, then what's the problem? Here's the catch, some workflow and forms do not require the resource object, just the object id is enough to trigger an action. Example of such actions are delete, update, etc... These views do not contain a get_object method, and hence, we have no way of getting the information we need unless we make an API call. As it stands, at this point in time, I do not know if replacing the id and a name is possible for all views."}, {'account_id': 5623, 'date': '2015-01-27 15:09:34.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

commit_message:
Breadcrumbs for all pages

Navigating through pages will now leave a trail of breadcrumbs behind.
This provides a mechanism for user to go back to the previous screen.

Currently enabled for all pages except for identity projects because the
page for the project information does not actually exist.

Change-Id: Iad71c386a9927872dddea02997d867fd6eb33f07
Implements: blueprint breadcrumbs

commit_message:
Handle KeyManager exception when deleting a volume

This patch adds exception handler when deleting key of an encryption volume.
Raise 400 invalid volume instead of 500 to give the user a better understanding
why deleting failed.

Closes-bug: #1482120
Change-Id: I591f65823d1f212e92434323905cc9c4fbe6fd96

commit_message:
test_shelve_instance: cleanup class scope variable usage

This removes the class variables for keypair and security group
so we don't rely on tight coupling between method calls.

Change-Id: I8cdec35cbf3ca168c3d9979a771caa7221d4b511
Related-Bug: #1482299

commit_message:
test_stamp_pattern: cleanup class scope variable usage

This removes the class variables for keypair and security group
so we don't rely on tight coupling between method calls.

Change-Id: I24149494a42c3c2988c1f6b9ef9b8541ed65dc06
Related-Bug: #1482299

commit_message:
Use assertTrue/False instead of assertEqual(T/F)

The usage of assertEqual(True/False, ***) should be changed to a more
meaningful format of assertTrue/False(***).

Change-Id: I685f7bb0b4669d8813ebbb796b6014ad44d7ff0c
Closes-Bug: #1510001

   - To add more driver_infoes into this function. For instance, i will add iscsi and agent drivers support into os-cloud-config. So, without this refactoring patch, there will be a lot of if-else statments.

   >I do have one comment inline about the function mapping dict that I'd like addressed, but otherwise lgtm.

commit_message:
Refactor _extract_driver_info() to reduce complexity.

Split _extract_driver_info() into several tiny methods to reduce complexity.
Or it will be too complex while some new drivers are added later.
(For instance: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/188717/)

Change-Id: I989321575499bf61d4f08d289230d40d374d02ed

commit_message:
Retype enhancement for EMC VNX cinder driver

VNX driver will trigger lun migration when retyping a thin/thick
volume to a compressed volume and it is time-consuming. To enhance
the performance, this patch will directly turn on the compression
on a volume instead of migrating it.

Change-Id: I155272d1130ac0048d226742970e021118f2f123
Closes-Bug: #1495802

commit_message:
Add mistral-dashboard into projects in murano-congress gate

After merging https://review.openstack.org/#/c/225437/ by mistral
our gate-murano-congress-dsvm gate became broken due additional
installation of mistral-dashboard
This patch adds mistral-dashboard into projects variable for
this gate.

commit_message:
Do not copy sources

We do not need to copy source files anymore with current
openstackdocstheme, unset html_show_sourcelink and html_copy_source
links. Report a bug works without these as well.

This reduces the amount of files we build and publish (for Install Guide
from 42 MB to 39 MB), and thus speeds up building (from 44 to 41s for
Install Guide) slightly.

Change-Id: I666caaddf864876fc85145381d995297008b0e9a

Docs.o.o nav updates to sync with o.o

As part of the summit, we're launching some shiny new sections
of openstack.org. This patch keeps the nav bar at docs.o.o update
with the rest of o.o.

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-17 03:59:46.000000000', 'message': 'Don't add non-existant hosts to host aggrgrates

nova will throw an error if you attempt to add a node to a host
aggergate that does not "exist" in terms of nova. Therefore
depending on the order in which your nodes come up, you can have puppet
attempting to add a node to a host aggrgate when the node does not yet
have nova compute installed and "registered". This is especially true if
you manage your host list with a hiera list or other mechanism that is
not directly tied to nova-compute being installed. Instead of blowing up
with an error, we will instead print a warning and let eventual
consistency solve it as your nodes are installed.

Change-Id: I6249cd070ad804c626d880decb6767e2ff14dcbd

commit_message:
Don't add non-existent hosts to host aggregates

nova will throw an error if you attempt to add a node to a host
aggergate that does not "exist" in terms of nova. Therefore
depending on the order in which your nodes come up, you can have puppet
attempting to add a node to a host aggregate when the node does not yet
have nova compute installed and "registered". This is especially true if
you manage your host list with a hiera list or other mechanism that is
not directly tied to nova-compute being installed. Instead of blowing up
with an error, we will instead print a warning and let eventual
consistency solve it as your nodes are installed.

Since it is inefficient to call nova host-list once for every member of
a host aggregate we also cache this information and similarly cache the
output of nova aggegrate-details which previously was also called
once for every member of every aggegrate.

Change-Id: I6249cd070ad804c626d880decb6767e2ff14dcbd

[{'created': '2015-10-06 23:20:37.000000000', 'message': 'Do no use disabled as default replication_status

The V1 implementation of replication added a replication_status
field to the Volume object and set it to disabled by default on
volume creation.

This is problematic, because there's no way for the API or any
caller to know if the status is disabled because it was
explicitly set that way, or if it is because the back end or
volume-type do not support replication.

This results in cases like enable replication (which does a status
check on disabled) to be called inappropriately on devices that
don't support replication.

This patch modifies the default replication-status to "not-configured",
so there is a clear distinction between disabled and not-supported etc.
It's the responsibility of the driver to return the replication-status
update from create_volume when appropriate.

Change-Id: I943be2aef3b7c32026278f311dae9f82194372fe
Closes-Bug: #1503439

commit_message:
Verify volume is replication capable

The V1 implementation of replication added a replication_status
field to the Volume object and set it to disabled by default on
volume creation.

This is problematic, because there's no way for the API or any
caller to know if the status is disabled because it was
explicitly set that way, or if it is because the back end or
volume-type do not support replication.

This results in cases like enable replication (which does a status
check on disabled) to be called inappropriately on devices that
don't support replication.

This patch adds a decorator to the new replication methods which will
check that the volume is of type with replication_enabled=True before
attempting any replication related operations.

Change-Id: I943be2aef3b7c32026278f311dae9f82194372fe

commit_message:
Prepare `nailgun-net-check` package

Prepare `nailgun-net-check` package to upload it to `pypi`. It is
required for `fuelmenu`. So it will be added to the `requirements.txt`
when it will be available on `pypi`.

Move content of `setup.py` file to `setup.cfg` file.

Add `Makefile` for quick and handy `release` command.

Some changes (files) were taken from `openstack-dev/cookiecutter.git`.

Change-Id: Ia9119ac924f203cc814c986c9adb760baa461b90
Partial-Bug: #1502047

commit_message:
All offline nodes are removed as failed nodes

remove_failed_nodes took only newly deployed nodes uids into
consideration for checking for offline nodes. Now all nodes in cluster
are checked for being available.

Change-Id: Ifbdec3d6f8cd1b2751afb45c185efd5c5316a817
Closes-bug: #1502295

commit_message:
Add theme fix for browsable source code

This adds a fix to ensure that the published docs have the correct
link to the browsable source code as implemented in
https://review.openstack.org/236091

It also updates the dev-requirements for the docs jobs to ensure
that the requirements are in line with upstream.

It also includes an exclusion of the doc directory from the pep8
check as the documentation conf.py requires a lengthy line.

Change-Id: I7c434b9963391cc89779e90aa24cc4106b4f3534

commit_message:
Add fast format option for thick volume creation

Add option for user to disable fast format at thick
provisioned volume creation in IBM Storwize cinder.
The default value is False and clients who do not want
to do Fast Format for thick volume, they can set this
parameter to True.

DocImpact: Add fast format option
Change-Id: Ib627696b91c336d09de6066ee70ee518fca5a7a9
Closes-Bug: 1502404

commit_message:
Make getting token revocation list 9x faster on Mysql

For Mysql, (valid, expires) key is better than (expires, valid)
for getting token revocation list query.

If both exist, it will pick up (valid, expires):
explain SELECT token.id AS token_id, token.expires AS token_expires FROM
token WHERE token.expires > '2015-10-22 00:10:31.499464' AND token.valid
= 0;

1 SIMPLE  token range ix_token_expires_valid,ix_token_valid_expires
ix_token_valid_expires  6 NULL  49  Using where; Using index

Did a real test on a one million token table node, it is about:

70ms vs 600ms

Change-Id: If0d1ef0ff783e06db857adb3b0e1b96325b23328

That is good.  IMHO it would be better if we also found a way to say that DevStack+Neutron are *known* to not work on Ubuntu 15.04; the existing statement only denies knowledge, inviting the uninitiated to waste time trying it.'}, {'account_id': 4656, 'date': '2015-10-21 19:31:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

The problem is this happens every year when Ubuntu releases a new version. People download an iso, run devstack, and if something doesn't work they file a bug and fix. Having documentation that says DevStack works with X version would easily get stale."}, {'account_id': 8328, 'date': '2015-10-21 20:09:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

On reviewing the existing comment about operating system and version, step 1 of http://docs.openstack.org/developer/devstack/#quick-start , I see that it does not now match what I was remembering.  Regarding the current statement: it is silent about later versions of Ubuntu and the redhatverse.  I am suggesting it would be helpful to specifically *dis*courage people from trying OpSys.versions that we know will *NOT* work.  Some of us are doing work that goes better with more recent kernels, so we are motivated to try later opsys versions if there is a possibility that it might work.

It may be true that statements of what *does* work can rot, (a) I am not suggesting we add any and (b) there already are some (thankfully!).'}, {'account_id': 4656, 'date': '2015-10-27 07:15:01.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

squashed into parent patch'}]

commit_message:
Fedora no longer packages OpenStack

This patch removes reference to fedora from the ops:packaged
tag description. RHEL and Fedora always had different packaging,
but now fedora has chosen to no longer package OpenStack.

From https://review.openstack.org/#/c/237509/ :

According to
https://www.redhat.com/archives/rdo-list/2015-October/msg00234.html
OpenStack packages for Fedora will only provided through the
Delorean repository.

More details at https://trello.com/c/wzdl1IlZ/52-openstack-in-fedora:

---snip---
Fedora users (assumed to be developers who want latest code and not
running production) will use Delorean Trunk for Fedora repos.
---snap---

Change-Id: I193eda813c16e202490b4c0e09c6ec816ca5a612

commit_message:
Port image cache to Python 3

* Replace [unicode, str] with six.string_types and use isinstance()
  to check the type
* tox.ini: add cinder.tests.unit.image.test_cache to Python 3.4

Partial-Implements: blueprint cinder-python3

[{'created': '2015-10-22 20:15:21.000000000', 'message': '[Kubernetes] Bunch of issues regarding scaling was fixed

1. There was scaleGatewayUp but no Down action
2. Gracefully remove node from etcd upon down-scale of nodes/gateways
3. Log to user which gateways were created/deleted
4. Deployment either hanged or worked incorrectly when downscaling and then
     upscaling something again

Also sets minimum gateway node count to 1 until gateway-less mode be fully
functional again

Change-Id: Ie3255f70b8a3fdfadab119a579c00433938495c8
Closes-Bug: #1509074
'}]
commit_message:
[Kubernetes] Bunch of issues regarding scaling was fixed

1. There was scaleGatewayUp but no Down action
2. Gracefully remove node from etcd upon down-scale of nodes/gateways
3. Log to user which gateways were created/deleted
4. Deployment either hanged or worked incorrectly when downscaling and then
     upscaling something again

Also sets minimum gateway node count to 1 until gateway-less mode be fully
functional again

Change-Id: Ie3255f70b8a3fdfadab119a579c00433938495c8
Closes-Bug: #1509074

commit_message:
Use ClientPlugin.ignore_not_found as a context manager

These are all trivial uses with no flow control implications, where using a
context manager is clearly simpler.

Change-Id: I908c34738f8881787ea697c7378dcf2f17f6e7fc

commit_message:
Include alembic versions directory to the package

If package is built without access to git metadata, all the migration
scripts are not included in the build. We need to explicitly specify to
package the scripts.

This patch also removes non-existing files from MANIFEST.in

Change-Id: I9a2acad13271863ee94de63c2404e8697ea70601
Related-bug: #1505628

commit_message:
Fix docstring

Fix docstring in _get_token_id that explains that it will raise a
NotImplemented error when in fact it can never raise a
NotImplemented error. As well as the docstring inconsistencies
throughout this file.

Change-Id: I8de39e76b92fe9a89b21dfeaf3824e39639827de

commit_message:
l3: Stop mimicing a core plugin

Due to a bug in the recent Neutron change, [1]
NeutronDbPluginV2 inheritance here makes RPC worker crash.
Remove the inheritance as it isn't appropriate for non-core plugins.

[1] I6fea7f409c91b25d2c35b038d6100fdfa85d1905

Closes-Bug: #1509409
Related-Bug: #1509892
Change-Id: Ie5edafff3d107908e0d349c7c711e427d7fec243

commit_message:
Updated the repo build templates

The change makes it so the upper constraints file is created
specifically using the repos indexed and cloned. Previously the
constraint file was created using the git repos found within the
local openstackgit directory and while that works for greenfield
deployments it does have the potential to create additional entries
that may or may not work with an environment.

The manifest file now uses normalized file names and will track the
exact git repos needed to power a build. This will allow for more
targetted syncs from an upstream mirror to happen using the
`repo-clone-mirror.yml` play.

The venv build process will now check for a prebuilt venv using the
versioned file name.

Change-Id: If4416f660133a6c65badba0c7c819a6409bfe11e
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>
(cherry picked from commit d7f496601f3ba99d1c02a940153e5e94915b0c31)

commit_message:
Warn vanilla 2.6.0 instead of raising exception

The vanilla 2.6.0 plugin is now deprecated and will be removed in
M release, but for now, 2.6.0 is still being used by many users like
me, we should remove 2.6.0 smoothly, so I think it's more comfortable
to log a warning instead of raising an exception.

Change-Id: I012a01226310b873852eaa978aaf2c91b9197c90
Closes-Bug: #1495767

commit_message:
Port IBM flashsystem to Python 3

* Replace dict.keys()[0] with list(dict.keys())[0]. On Python 3,
  dict.keys() now returns a view which is not indexable.
* tests-py3.txt: add cinder.tests.unit.test_ibm_flashsystem

Partial-Implements: blueprint cinder-python3
Change-Id: Ic77145784acc8c88e77d50a5086019e69d15e6ff

commit_message:
db: Use postgresql lib class for psycopg package

This patch introduce the same design than mysql for postgresql
by requiring dedicated lib::python class instead of declaring
a new resource package within aodh module.

This patch also add unit tests for aodh::db class.

Change-Id: I3f9ed49b44a9a7c89be06f40a5823cc24a66066e

commit_message:
Add oslo_config IPOpt support

As oslo_config profides IPOpt type to validate the range of ip now,
we could change bind_host to IPOpt from StrOpt.

Change-Id: I688df6e10c3ced29b5b361752ee5a3e8fbff9f40
Closes-bug: #1510348

@Li Ma
_kill_process is named as a "private" method, so if caller in AsyncProcess doesn't use its return value, I couldn't see why we still need the return value.

And this patch also removes a useless UT case, seems you didn't know that.'}, {'account_id': 7805, 'date': '2015-10-23 01:21:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Firstly, I understand what you wanna do. However, after I read the context, I think there's no problem for _kill_process, but the caller doesn't do the right job.

When a process is killed by signal but isn't dead as expected (it really happens in the real world), we can only collect error from log file and the program definitely runs into a problem. This because _kill_process returns the state but the caller ignores it. So we don't know whether the process is still running or becomes dead.

I remove -1, not because this is good for neutron, but because your work doesn't make it worse."}, {'account_id': 7805, 'date': '2015-10-23 01:21:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: -Code-Review'}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2015-10-23 08:25:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
remove useless return value for _kill_process

Class AsyncProcess method _kill_process return
value are useless, they are just used in UT.
Use mock to replace checking return value.

Also remove unnecessary UT case
test_kill_process_with_different_signal and
redefine _test__kill_process, sinse
utils.execute is mocked, there is no difference
to different pids and signals.

Closes-Bug: #1508530
Change-Id: I19803e95b1390dbe08f735ab302e2ebc9b0d7454

commit_message:
mitaka: release python-novaclient 2.33.0

The 2.32.0 release had d045019f0f2d28f26730b3617f7d7b993506b6e8 which
introduced bug 1508244 that is fixed with
28bf8ddb06a618bec280c9fbc21b4be6af2c1787 so we need to put out a new
release for that fix.

This is a minor version bump because of dependency updates, support for
microversion 2.6 was added.

Changes since 2.32.0:

217e7c1 Updated from global requirements
2961e82 Do not expose exceptions from requests library
cce7cd3 Support the server side remote-console API changes
28bf8dd Correct usage of API_MAX_VERSION and
DEFAULT_OS_COMPUTE_API_VERSION
727f104 Rely on devstack for clouds.yaml
262719d Updated from global requirements
1c401ed Updated from global requirements
a820c45 Use v2.0 in clouds.yaml auth_url for functional test job
afaa8a2 Increase timeout when testing admin timeout
d10486f Fix incorrect help for 'nova flavor-create'

Change-Id: Iad905cc29d6f1a3571f1245ca18078855a50178b

commit_message:
Add warning suppression for keystoneauth loggers

In our simple_logging helper function, add a null logger for
keystoneauth base auth plugin to suppress the "no handler found"
warning.

commit_message:
Fix argument order in assertEqual to (expect, obs)

assertEqual expects that the arguments provided to it should be
(expected, observed). If a particular order is kept as a convention,
then it helps to provide a cleaner message to the developer if Unit Tests
fail. There are several Unit Test files where the arguments for assertEqual
have been swapped.

Closes-Bug: #1259292
Change-Id: I17930c8ba8168baba9baddbdb7a54d54497f6a6d

commit_message:
Suppress Rackspace SAN warnings again

The old warning suppression stopped working because the string
from urllib changed. Instead of using that, use the actual warning
class in the suppression.

Change-Id: Ib06516ffb5b2cc272d597e7eac959dd39e27c3a4

commit_message:
Fix percona-xtrabackup issue with backup tests

It appears that a recent new version of
percona-xtrabackup has broken the backup tests.

This fix pins the version of xtrabackup to 2.2

Change-Id: I5e838b60dd5c9d7254c6a2c1177257bcd9f6da73
Closes-Bug:#1509551

commit_message:
Add system architecture detail in Ironic Section

Since Ironic is an integration project now. We should add one section
about it in Admin guide.
This commit is part of the bugfix since adding the whole section is
huge. This one is to add detail about system architecture.

commit_message:
Add doc publishing/buildings jobs for anvil

Publish the docs for anvil into the openstack
documentation tree, this will allow for the deletion
and removal of http://anvil.readthedocs.org/ which
serves the sames purpose.

commit_message:
Check dashboard symlinks during horizon plugin installation

This patch add '-f' flag to horizon plugin symlink generation.
It helps to prevent deployment fails if symlink already exists.

Change-Id: I94ece2689c9b7332958e32788b5531d540b063f8
Closes-Bug: #1508023

messages:

- gate-sdk-dsvm-functional http://logs.openstack.org/73/220273/1/check/gate-sdk-dsvm-functional/516d777/ : FAILURE in 29m 01s (non-voting)'}, {'account_id': 8257, 'date': '2015-09-15 17:00:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I don't know if I agree with the premise of the change. The results of a repr should be able to be fed back into eval so that the same object can be created. While loaded=False is the default in the initializer, and its removal from the repr would still currently allow the same object to be created, we'd be depending on that default argument always being what it is. If it changed to a default True for some reason, we'd have a broken repr.

I think this change ends up complicating the repr in exchange for something only slightly more visually appealing.

I'm not -2 strong against this, but I don't get a lot of the value of this. We're bound to similar things with nested resources where they're just not as clearly readable due to duplicate names, but that's just the nature of having objects created from other objects."}, {'account_id': 8736, 'date': '2015-09-15 17:06:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

This certainly isn't a huge deal, but when you look at a repr of a resource that has a resource, it is very confusing what is going on.  This just makes it a lot more readable for humans."}, {'account_id': 8257, 'date': '2015-09-15 17:14:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I'm blanking on a concrete example at the moment, but this could end up covering differences in the loaded status of a parent resource and its child resources. For example, if you do a get_foo and end up with a foo, then do foo.something = Something(...), the repr of foo with this change wouldn't reflect that the foo itself has been loaded via the get_foo call, but the foo.something resource has not been loaded since it only exists locally."}, {'account_id': 8736, 'date': '2015-09-15 17:24:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Kind of looks like:

    Object(name=foo, container=Container(name=bar, loaded=True), loaded=True)

A real example would be better, but I just kept looking at it wondering what the heck it is.'}, {'account_id': 8257, 'date': '2015-09-15 18:16:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

There's going to be a lot more duplicated when you look at something like a Server, since it'll have the nested Image and Flavor, so we'll have three names, three ids, three loadeds, etc. I would probably prefer we just leave this and represent the objects as they are. It doesn't seem worth the added complexity to the repr function."}, {'account_id': 8736, 'date': '2015-10-26 22:45:52.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

To make the string representation of the resource more readable,
only print loaded if it is True.  The value of loaded defaults to
False, so if it isn't in the string representation, we should still
be able to create a valid resource.

Printing of resources gets more confusing when there is a resource

"}]
commit_message:
Only repr resource loaded field if it is True

To make the string representation of the resource more readable,
only print loaded if it is True.  The value of loaded defaults to
False, so if it isn't in the string representation, we should still
be able to create a valid resource.

Printing of resources gets more confusing when there is a resource
in a resource and in that case you get two loaded values next to
each other.

Change-Id: I37f0e6096be83cf5b09c51d2fa173f9e1dddd4a6

I'm not too happy with the standard format of functional tests
because it seems busy using setUpClass and tearDownClass and
those methods do not get access to methods such as assertEqual.
This approach relies on two things:

1) The create is named ascibetically first in this case test_aaa
   and the delete is last test_zzz.
2) Class variables are used for some values that need to be
   communicated between classes.

It looks a little cleaner.  Biggest downside is you cannot run
just test_find because test_aaa needs to be run to create the
network.

commit_message:
Try out another functional test standard

I'm not too happy with the standard format of functional tests
because it seems busy using setUpClass and tearDownClass and
those methods do not get access to methods such as assertEqual.
This approach relies on two things:

1) The delete must be named asciibetically last in this case
   test_zzz.
2) Class variables are used for some values that need to be
   communicated between classes.

It looks a little cleaner.

Change-Id: I2d56ee7d8cbdc2c48f5efa9a98f4c06ddcbf37e3

commit_message:
return additional detail about servers

Introduce a new parameter `detailed` to `list_servers`,
`search_servers`, and `get_server`.  When True, `list_servers` will call
`meta.get_hostvars_from_server` for each server.

This does not modify the default behavior (`detailed=False`) of these
methods.

Change-Id: I919fd2ec20515c2b13eee02a75623c6ce6d7d273

commit_message:
expand security groups in get_hostvars_from_server

Add a call to `list_server_security_groups` to
`meta.get_hostvars_from_server`.  This replaces the minimal list of
security group names with detailed information that includes security
group ids.

Change-Id: I5a01b37efd5520205c6ce94f0fdc4c09f75053c2

commit_message:
Add general reference for IBM Style Guide

The IBM Style Guide is used not only for spelling but in general, add it
as general guideline.

Original wiki content was "This page lists conventions that the Docs
team follows for writing documentation. Additionally, the IBM Style
Guide is used as reference. In case of conflicts between these two, the
wiki convention pages takes precedence."

Change-Id: Ic308841a3ddb9551c2b80ea237ec587165d3c59d

commit_message:
Always pull regions from vendor profiles

Regions are special, since they're a driver for creating a cloud
config object in the first place. We weren't syncing them from
the vendor profile, so if the region wasn't set in the clouds.yaml,
region name validation (and get_all_clouds) would fail.

Change-Id: I5b8d6807a86b87a7f69f523f2fee2784389fab0a

[{'created': '2015-10-26 13:20:22.000000000', 'message': "Fix usage of setUpClass method in functional tests

Class method 'setUpClass' is executed for each test of test suite that
appeared in new thread. It leads to creation of redundant resources,
and, hence, waste of resources.

So, add 'group_regex' option in testr config that will make all tests
of each class run in one thread.

Change-Id: I8100a98961791cee52b0866c7d593cc8371b3329
Closes-Bug: #1509460
"}]
commit_message:
Fix usage of setUpClass method in functional tests

Class method 'setUpClass' is executed for each test of test suite that
appeared in new thread. It leads to creation of redundant resources,
and, hence, waste of resources.

So, add 'group_regex' option in testr config that will make all tests
of each class run in one thread.

Change-Id: I8100a98961791cee52b0866c7d593cc8371b3329
Closes-Bug: #1509460

commit_message:
Use 'restart' instead of 'start' to apply changes

httpd is already started, so we need to use 'restart' to apply
our changes to the configuration.

We also need to update the note to reflect the change.

Change-Id: Ic20c9e0cbf01521cd8135163874690577b9e9769
Partial-Bug: #1467994

commit_message:
Check gateways if non-default node groups are used

Add neutron_check_gateways to NetworkCheck class which checks that
valid gateways are specified for all networks if non-default node
groups are used.

Change-Id: I433bc322bbfa2e121fba77ea9802d4a5d3a218ad
Closes-Bug: #1472662

commit_message:
Add support for enable/disable service API

Manila has API to enable or disable its services for long time.
Since fork from Cinder. But manilaclient does not have support for it.
So, add it.

Change-Id: I797e2e4201ba5d2d85d397834aeb0bee5e4240f5
Closes-Bug: #1499247

commit_message:
Cleanup hdisk on source post live migration

When a VM has volumes attached via vscsi, the hdisks on the
Virtual I/O servers that reside on the source host should
be cleaned up after the VM has been migrated to the desination
host.

Change-Id: I7f3d7afa8033190c5969f887f32d2f0c7ae0c66b
Closes-Bug: 1506960
(cherry picked from commit 903ceabb329b2f526a73e9a330a5bc74750fe048)

commit_message:
Support to launch instance booted from uefi rom for AARCH64/ARM

Currently qemu-system-arm or qemu-system-aarch64 needs '-bios ROM.bin'
for booting from uefi rom, unfortunately nova-compute can't build the
parameter for qumu via libvirt. This patch will fix this by specifying
the bios path when configing guest.

DocImpact: Adds a new config variable to specify bios rom path when
           booting from uefi rom.
Closes-bug: #1402889
Change-Id: If478548892f69f33d1b898d5b18846f40cf55974

commit_message:
Create symlinks instead of full copying

File/Dir driver executes 'cp' utility if being targeted to local
object.
There's no any reason to use 'cp' as shotgun doesn't need to have a
full copy of targeted object.

In order to reduce waste of disk space and i/o resouces,
for local target shotgun will recreate directory structure and
create symlinks for all files into it.

Change-Id: If1420173c2b01d0d4845034cf0d683005a8ee1a3
Closes-Bug: #1445311

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-07 21:28:59.000000000', 'message': 'Port _transfer_data() to Python 3

* Replace xrange() with range(). This file uses
  "from six.moves import range", so "range" is xrange on Python 2.
* Break the loop when src.read() returns an empty byte string, not an
  empty Unicode string.

Note: test_volume_utils already runs on Python 3, but it looks like
the modified function _transfer_data() is not directly by this file.
Hopefuly, it's tested indirectly by other tests.

Partial-Implements: blueprint cinder-python3
Change-Id: Ib69b9ee4669d3b627747c754b1bda1994f0ed2a5
'}, {'created': '2015-10-08 15:41:56.000000000', 'message': 'Port ceph driver to Python 3

* Replace xrange() with range(). cinder/volume/utils.py uses
  "from six.moves import range", so "range" is xrange on Python 2.
* Replace '' with b'' for image content to get a bytes string on
  Python 3.

Note: _transfer_data() of cinder.volume.utils is tested by
test_backup_ceph which is already run on Python 3, but the test only

commit_message:
Port ceph driver to Python 3

* Replace xrange() with range(). cinder/volume/utils.py uses
  "from six.moves import range", so "range" is xrange on Python 2.
* Replace '' with b'' for image content to get a bytes string on
  Python 3.

Note: _transfer_data() of cinder.volume.utils is tested by
test_backup_ceph which is already run on Python 3, but the test only
failed with python3 run with -bb. This bug is now fixed.

Partial-Implements: blueprint cinder-python3
Change-Id: Ib69b9ee4669d3b627747c754b1bda1994f0ed2a5
